# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: neuroanatomy
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The **basal ganglia** (**BG**) or **basal nuclei** are a group of subcortical nuclei (cluster of neurons) found in the brains of vertebrates.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Positioned at the base of the forebrain and the top of the midbrain, they have strong connections with the cerebral cortex, thalamus, brainstem and other brain areas.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The basal ganglia are associated with a variety of functions, including regulating voluntary motor movements, procedural learning, habit formation, conditional learning, eye movements, cognition, and emotion.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Each of these components has complex internal anatomical and neurochemical structures.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The largest component, the striatum (dorsal and ventral), receives input from various brain areas but only sends output to other components of the basal ganglia.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The globus pallidus receives input from the striatum and sends inhibitory output to a number of motor-related areas.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The substantia nigra is the source of the striatal input of the neurotransmitter dopamine, which plays an important role in basal ganglia function.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The subthalamic nucleus mainly receives input from the striatum and cerebral cortex and projects to the globus pallidus.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The basal ganglia are thought to play a key role in action selection, aiding in the choice of behaviors to execute.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] More specifically, they regulate motor and premotor cortical areas, facilitating smooth voluntary movements.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Experimental studies show that the basal ganglia exert an inhibitory influence on a number of motor systems, and that a release of this inhibition permits a motor system to become active.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The "behavior switching" that takes place within the basal ganglia is influenced by signals from many parts of the brain, including the prefrontal cortex, which plays a key role in executive functions.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] It has also been hypothesized that the basal ganglia are not only responsible for motor action selection, but also for the selection of more cognitive actions.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Computational models of action selection in the basal ganglia incorporate this.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The basal ganglia are of major importance for normal brain function and behaviour.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Their dysfunction results in a wide range of neurological conditions including disorders of behaviour control and movement, as well as cognitive deficits that are similar to those that result from damage to the prefrontal cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Those of behaviour include Tourette syndrome, obsessive–compulsive disorder, and addiction.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Movement disorders include, most notably Parkinson's disease, which involves degeneration of the dopamine-producing cells in the substantia nigra; Huntington's disease, which primarily involves damage to the striatum; dystonia; and more rarely hemiballismus.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The basal ganglia have a limbic sector whose components are assigned distinct names: the nucleus accumbens, ventral pallidum, and ventral tegmental area (VTA).
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] There is considerable evidence that this limbic part plays a central role in reward learning as well as cognition and frontal lobe functioning, via the mesolimbic pathway from the VTA to the nucleus accumbens that uses the neurotransmitter dopamine, and the mesocortical pathway.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] A number of highly addictive drugs, including cocaine, amphetamine, and nicotine, are thought to work by increasing the efficacy of this dopamine signal.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] There is also evidence implicating overactivity of the VTA dopaminergic projection in schizophrenia.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Later in development each section itself turns into smaller components.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] During development, the cells that migrate tangentially to form the basal ganglia are directed by the lateral and medial ganglionic eminences.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The following table demonstrates this developmental classification and traces it to the anatomic structures found in the basal ganglia.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The structures relevant to the basal ganglia are shown in **bold**.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The basal ganglia form a fundamental component of the cerebrum.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] In contrast to the cortical layer that lines the surface of the forebrain, the basal ganglia are a collection of distinct masses of gray matter lying deep in the brain not far from the junction of the thalamus.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] They lie to the side of and surround the thalamus.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Like most parts of the brain, the basal ganglia consist of left and right sides that are virtual mirror images of each other.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] In the illustration to the right, two coronal sections of the human brain show the location of the basal ganglia components.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Of note, and not seen in this section, the subthalamic nucleus and substantia nigra lie farther back (posteriorly) in the brain than the striatum and pallidum.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The striatum is a subcortical structure generally divided into the dorsal striatum and ventral striatum.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The dorsal striatum is further divided into a dorsomedial and dorsolateral striatum.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The striatum is composed mostly of medium spiny neurons.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] These GABAergic neurons project to the external (lateral) globus pallidus and internal (medial) globus pallidus as well as the substantia nigra pars reticulata.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The projections into the globus pallidus and substantia nigra are primarily dopaminergic, although enkephalin, dynorphin and substance P are expressed.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The dorsal striatum receives significant glutamatergic inputs from the cortex, as well as dopaminergic inputs from the substantia nigra pars compacta.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The dorsal striatum is generally considered to be involved in sensorimotor activities.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The ventral striatum receives glutamatergic inputs from the limbic areas as well as dopaminergic inputs from the VTA, via the mesolimbic pathway.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The ventral striatum is believed to play a role in reward and other limbic functions.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The dorsal striatum is divided into the caudate and putamen by the internal capsule while the ventral striatum is composed of the nucleus accumbens and olfactory tubercle.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The caudate has three primary regions of connectivity, with the head of the caudate demonstrating connectivity to the prefrontal cortex, cingulate cortex and amygdala.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The body and tail show differentiation between the dorsolateral rim and ventral caudate, projecting to the sensorimotor and limbic regions of the striatum respectively.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Striatopallidal fibres connect the striatum to the pallidus.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The pallidum consists of a large structure called the globus pallidus ("pale globe") together with a smaller ventral extension called the ventral pallidum.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The globus pallidus appears as a single neural mass, but can be divided into two functionally distinct parts, the internal globus pallidus (GPi) and the external globus pallidus (GPe).
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Both segments contain primarily GABAergic neurons, which therefore have inhibitory effects on their targets.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The two segments participate in distinct neural circuits.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The GPe receives input mainly from the striatum, and projects to the subthalamic nucleus.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The GPi receives signals from the striatum via the "direct" and "indirect" pathways.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Pallidal neurons operate using a disinhibition principle.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] These neurons fire at steady high rates in the absence of input, and signals from the striatum cause them to pause or reduce their rate of firing.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Because pallidal neurons themselves have inhibitory effects on their targets, the net effect of striatal input to the pallidum is a reduction of the tonic inhibition exerted by pallidal cells on their targets (disinhibition) with an increased rate of firing in the targets.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The substantia nigra is a midbrain gray matter portion of the basal ganglia that has two parts – the pars compacta (SNc) and the pars reticulata (SNr).
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] SNr often works in unison with GPi, and the SNr–GPi complex inhibits the thalamus.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Substantia nigra pars compacta (SNc) however, produces the neurotransmitter dopamine, which is very significant in maintaining balance in the striatal pathway.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The circuit portion below explains the role and circuit connections of each of the components of the basal ganglia.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The subthalamic nucleus is a diencephalic gray matter portion of the basal ganglia, and the only portion of the ganglia that produces an excitatory neurotransmitter, glutamate.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The role of the subthalamic nucleus is to stimulate the SNr–GPi complex and it is part of the indirect pathway.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The subthalamic nucleus receives inhibitory input from the external part of the globus pallidus and sends excitatory input to the GPi.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Multiple models of basal ganglia circuits and function have been proposed, though questions have been raised about the strict divisions of the direct and indirect pathways, their possible overlap and regulation.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The circuitry model has evolved since the first proposed model in the 1990s by DeLong in the parallel *processing model*, in which the cortex and substantia nigra pars compacta project into the dorsal striatum giving rise to an inhibitory indirect and excitatory direct pathway.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] While implemented as a gradient without exact borders (or septa within the nuclei), the basal ganglia circuitry has often been divided into five pathways: one limbic, two associative (prefrontal), one oculomotor, and one motor pathway.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The motor and oculomotor pathways are sometimes grouped into one motor pathway.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Furthermore, a simplified scheme into three domains (motor, associative and limbic) has gained popularity.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] These circuits are known to interact (at least) on a cortico-cortical level (U-fibers), a cortico-striatal level (by diffuse projections from cortex to striatum), a thalamo-cortical level (by diffuse reciprocal connections across thalamus and cortex) and striato-nigral level.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] In this model, connections from the ventral tegmental area to the shell region of the nucleus accumbens form a "closed," reciprocal loop.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] However, these projections also extend laterally to influence dopamine neurons that send signals to the rest of the ventral striatum, creating the initial segment of a feed-forward loop, or 'spiral'.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] This spiral continues through striato-nigro-striatal pathways, whereby the VS affects cognitive and motor striatal areas via midbrain dopamine neurons.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The direct pathway, originating in the dorsal striatum inhibits the GPi and SNr, resulting in a net disinhibition or excitation of the thalamus.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] This pathway consists of medium spiny neurons (MSNs) that express dopamine receptor D1, muscarinic acetylcholine receptor M4, and adenosine receptor A1.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The direct pathway has been proposed to facilitate motor actions, timing of motor actions, gating of working memory, and motor responses to specific stimuli.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The (long) indirect pathway originates in the dorsal striatum and inhibits the GPe, resulting in disinhibition of the GPi which is then free to inhibit the thalamus.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] This pathway consists of MSNs that express dopamine receptor D2, muscarinic acetylcholine receptor M1, and adenosine receptor A2a.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] This pathway has been proposed to result in global motor inhibition(inhibition of all motor activity), and termination of responses.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Another shorter indirect pathway has been proposed, which involves cortical excitation of the subthalamic nucleus resulting in direct excitation of the GPe, and inhibition of the thalamus.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] This pathway is proposed to result in inhibition of specific motor programs based on associative learning.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] A combination of these indirect pathways resulting in a hyperdirect pathway that results in inhibition of basal ganglia inputs besides one specific focus has been proposed as part of the *center surround theory*.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] This hyperdirect pathway is proposed to inhibit premature responses, or globally inhibit the basal ganglia to allow for more specific top down control by the cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The interactions of these pathways are currently under debate.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Some say that all pathways directly antagonize each other in a "push pull" fashion, while others support the *center surround theory*, in which one focused input into the cortex is protected by inhibition of competing inputs by the rest of the indirect pathways.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The basal ganglia receive many afferent glutamatergic inputs, with predominantly GABAergic efferent fibers, modulatory cholinergic pathways, significant dopamine in the pathways originating in the ventral tegmental area and substantia nigra, as well as various neuropeptides.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Neuropeptides found in the basal ganglia include substance P, neurokinin A, cholecystokinin, neurotensin, neurokinin B, neuropeptide Y, somatostatin, dynorphin, enkephalin.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Other neuromodulators found in the basal ganglia include nitric oxide, carbon monoxide, and phenethylamine.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The functional connectivity, measured by regional co-activation during functional neuroimaging studies, is broadly consistent with the parallel processing models of basal ganglia function.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The putamen was generally coactivated with motor areas such as the supplementary motor area, caudal anterior cingulate cortex and primary motor cortex, while the caudate and rostral putamen were more frequently coactivated with the rostral ACC and DLPFC.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The ventral striatum was significantly associated with the amygdala and hippocampus, which although was not included in the first formulations of basal ganglia models, has been an addition to more recent models.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] One intensively studied function of the basal ganglia is its role in controlling eye movements.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Eye movement is influenced by an extensive network of brain regions that converges on a midbrain area called the superior colliculus (SC).
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The SC is a layered structure whose layers form two-dimensional retinotopic maps of visual space.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] A "bump" of neural activity in the deep layers of the SC drives an eye movement directed toward the corresponding point in space.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The SC receives a strong inhibitory projection from the basal ganglia, originating in the substantia nigra pars reticulata (SNr).
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Neurons in the SNr usually fire continuously at high rates, but at the onset of an eye movement they "pause", thereby releasing the SC from inhibition.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Eye movements of all types are associated with "pausing" in the SNr; however, individual SNr neurons may be more strongly associated with some types of movements than others.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Neurons in some parts of the caudate nucleus also show activity related to eye movements.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Since the great majority of caudate cells fire at very low rates, this activity almost always shows up as an increase in firing rate.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Thus, eye movements begin with activation in the caudate nucleus, which inhibits the SNr via the direct GABAergic projections, which in turn disinhibits the SC.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Extracellular dopamine in the basal ganglia has been linked to motivational states in rodents, with high levels being linked to satiated state, medium levels with seeking, and low with aversion.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The limbic basal ganglia circuits are influenced heavily by extracellular dopamine.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Increased dopamine results in inhibition of the Ventral pallidum, entopeduncular nucleus, and substantia nigra pars reticulata, resulting in disinhibition of the thalamus.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] This model of direct D1, and indirect D2 pathways explain why selective agonists of each receptor are not rewarding, as activity at both pathways is required for disinhibition.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The disinhibition of the thalamus leads to activation of the prefrontal cortex and ventral striatum, selective for increased D1 activity leading to reward.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] There is also evidence from non-human primate and human electrophysiology studies that other basal ganglia structures including the globus pallidus internus and subthalamic nucleus are involved in reward processing.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Two models have been proposed for the basal ganglia's role in decision making.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] In the first, actions are generated by a "critic" in the ventral striatum that estimates value, and the actions are carried out by an "actor" in the dorsal striatum.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] In the second, the basal ganglia acts as a selection mechanism, where actions are generated in the cortex and are selected based on context by the basal ganglia.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The CBGTC loop is also involved in reward discounting, with firing increasing with an unexpected or greater than expected reward.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] One review supported the idea that the cortex was involved in learning actions regardless of their outcome, while the basal ganglia was involved in selecting appropriate actions based on associative reward based trial and error learning.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The basal ganglia has been proposed to gate what does and does not enter working memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The short indirect pathway has been proposed to close the gate to the prefrontal cortex, in a direct push-pull antagonism with the direct pathway.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Together these mechanisms regulate working memory focus.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Basal ganglia disease is a group of movement disorders that result from either excessive output from the basal ganglia to the thalamus (for hypokinetic disorders), or from insufficient output (for hyperkinetic disorders).
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Hypokinetic disorders arise from an excessive output from the basal ganglia, which inhibits the output from the thalamus to the cortex, and thus limits voluntary movement.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Hyperkinetic disorders result from a low output from the basal ganglia to the thalamus which gives not enough inhibition to the thalamic projections to the cortex and thus gives uncontrolled/involuntary movements.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Dysfunction of the basal ganglia circuitry can also lead to other disorders.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] It took time for the basal ganglia to be accepted as constituting a system of functionally related brain nuclei.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The first anatomical identification of distinct subcortical structures was published by Thomas Willis in 1664.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] For many years, the term corpus striatum was used to describe a large group of subcortical elements, some of which were later discovered to be functionally unrelated.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Likewise, for many years, the putamen and the caudate nucleus were not associated with each other.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Instead, the putamen was associated with the pallidum in what was called the nucleus lenticularis or nucleus lentiformis.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] A thorough reconsideration by Cécile and Oskar Vogt (1941) simplified the description of the basal ganglia by proposing the term striatum to describe the group of structures consisting of the caudate nucleus, the putamen, and the mass linking them ventrally, the nucleus accumbens.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The striatum was named on the basis of the striated (striped) appearance created by radiating dense bundles of striato-pallido-nigral axons, described by anatomist Samuel Alexander Kinnier Wilson (1912) as "pencil-like".
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The anatomical link of the striatum with its primary targets, the pallidum and the substantia nigra, was discovered later.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The name *globus pallidus* was attributed to Burdach (1822) by Déjerine.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] For this, the Vogts proposed the simpler term *pallidum*.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The term *locus niger* was introduced by Félix Vicq-d'Azyr as *tache noire* in (1786), though that structure has since become known as the substantia nigra, due to contributions by Von Sömmering in 1788.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The structural similarity between the substantia nigra and globus pallidus was noted by Mirto in 1896.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Together, the two are known as the pallidonigral ensemble, which represents the core of the basal ganglia.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Altogether, the main structures of the basal ganglia are linked to each other by the striato-pallido-nigral bundle, which passes through the pallidum, crosses the internal capsule as the "comb bundle of Edinger", and finally reaches the substantia nigra.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Additional structures that later became associated with the basal ganglia are the "body of Luys" (1865) (or nucleus of Luys) or subthalamic nucleus, whose lesion was known to produce movement disorders.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] More recently, other areas such as the centromedian nucleus and the pedunculopontine complex have been thought to be regulators of the basal ganglia.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Near the beginning of the 20th century, the basal ganglia system was first associated with motor functions, as lesions of these areas would often result in disordered movement in humans (chorea, athetosis, Parkinson's disease).
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The nomenclature of the basal ganglia system and its components has always been problematic.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The term "basal" comes from the fact that most of its elements are located in the basal part of the forebrain.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The term ganglia is a misnomer: In modern usage, neural clusters are called "ganglia" only in the peripheral nervous system; in the central nervous system they are called "nuclei".
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] For this reason, the basal ganglia are also occasionally known as the "basal nuclei".
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] *Terminologia Anatomica* (1998), the international authority for anatomical naming, retained "nuclei basales", but this is not commonly used.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The International Basal Ganglia Society (IBAGS) informally considers the basal ganglia to be made up of the striatum, the pallidum (with two nuclei), the substantia nigra (with its two distinct parts), and the subthalamic nucleus, whereas Terminologia anatomica excludes the last two.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Some neurologists have included the centromedian nucleus of the thalamus as part of the basal ganglia, and some have also included the pedunculopontine nucleus.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The basal ganglia form one of the basic components of the forebrain, and can be recognized in all species of vertebrates.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] Even in the lamprey (generally considered one of the most primitive vertebrates), striatal, pallidal, and nigral elements can be identified on the basis of anatomy and histochemistry.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The names given to the various nuclei of the basal ganglia are different in different species.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] In cats and rodents the internal globus pallidus is known as the *entopeduncular nucleus*.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] In birds the striatum is called the *paleostriatum augmentatum* and the external globus pallidus is called the *paleostriatum primitivum*.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] A clear emergent issue in comparative anatomy of the basal ganglia is the development of this system through phylogeny as a convergent cortically re-entrant loop in conjunction with the development and expansion of the cortical mantle.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] There is controversy, however, regarding the extent to which convergent selective processing occurs versus segregated parallel processing within re-entrant closed loops of the basal ganglia.
[src:neuroanatomy/basal-ganglia] The abrupt rostral re-direction of the pathway from the internal segment of the globus pallidus into the ventral thalamus—via the path of the ansa lenticularis—could be viewed as a footprint of this evolutionary transformation of basal ganglia outflow and targeted influence.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The **cerebellum** (pl.: **cerebella** or **cerebellums**; Latin for 'little brain') is a major feature of the hindbrain of all vertebrates.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Although usually smaller than the cerebrum, in some animals such as the mormyrid fishes it may be as large as it or even larger.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] In humans, the cerebellum plays an important role in motor control and cognitive functions such as attention and language as well as emotional control such as regulating fear and pleasure responses, but its movement-related functions are the most solidly established.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The human cerebellum does not initiate movement, but contributes to motor coordination, precision, and accurate timing: it receives input from sensory systems of the spinal cord and from other parts of the brain, and integrates these inputs to fine-tune motor activity.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Cerebellar damage produces disorders in fine movement, equilibrium, posture, and motor learning in humans.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Anatomically, the human cerebellum has the appearance of a separate structure attached to the bottom of the brain, tucked underneath the cerebral hemispheres.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Its cortical surface is covered with finely spaced parallel grooves, in striking contrast to the broad irregular convolutions of the cerebral cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] These parallel grooves conceal the fact that the cerebellar cortex is actually a thin, continuous layer of tissue tightly folded in the style of an accordion.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Within this thin layer are several types of neurons with a highly regular arrangement, the most important being Purkinje cells and granule cells.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] This complex neural organization gives rise to a massive signal-processing capability, but almost all of the output from the cerebellar cortex passes through a set of small deep nuclei lying in the white matter interior of the cerebellum.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] In addition to its direct role in motor control, the cerebellum is necessary for several types of motor learning, most notably learning to adjust to changes in sensorimotor relationships.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Several theoretical models have been developed to explain sensorimotor calibration in terms of synaptic plasticity within the cerebellum.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The basic concept of the Marr–Albus theory is that the climbing fiber serves as a "teaching signal", which induces a long-lasting change in the strength of parallel fiber inputs.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Observations of long-term depression in parallel fiber inputs have provided some support for theories of this type, but their validity remains controversial.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] At the level of gross anatomy, the cerebellum consists of a tightly folded layer of cortex, with white matter underneath and a fluid-filled ventricle at the base.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Four deep cerebellar nuclei are embedded in the white matter.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Each part of the cortex consists of the same small set of neuronal elements, laid out in a highly stereotyped geometry.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] At an intermediate level, the cerebellum and its auxiliary structures can be separated into several hundred or thousand independently functioning modules called "microzones" or "microcompartments".
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The cerebellum is located in the posterior cranial fossa.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The fourth ventricle, pons and medulla are in front of the cerebellum.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] It is separated from the overlying cerebrum by a layer of leathery dura mater, the cerebellar tentorium; all of its connections with other parts of the brain travel through the pons.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Anatomists classify the cerebellum as part of the metencephalon, which also includes the pons; the metencephalon is the upper part of the rhombencephalon or "hindbrain".
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Like the cerebral cortex, the cerebellum is divided into two cerebellar hemispheres; it also contains a narrow midline zone (the vermis).
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] A set of large folds is, by convention, used to divide the overall structure into 10 smaller "lobules".
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Because of its large number of tiny granule cells, the cerebellum contains more neurons than the total from the rest of the brain, but takes up only 10% of the total brain volume.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The number of neurons in the cerebellum is related to the number of neurons in the neocortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] There are about 3.6 times as many neurons in the cerebellum as in the neocortex, a ratio that is conserved across many different mammalian species.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The unusual surface appearance of the cerebellum conceals the fact that most of its volume is made up of a very tightly folded layer of gray matter: the **cerebellar cortex**.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Each ridge or gyrus in this layer is called a **folium**.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] High‑resolution MRI finds the adult human cerebellar cortex has an area of 730 square cm, packed within a volume of dimensions 6 cm × 5 cm × 10 cm.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Underneath the gray matter of the cortex lies white matter, made up largely of myelinated nerve fibers running to and from the cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Embedded within the white matter—which is sometimes called the *arbor vitae* (tree of life) because of its branched, tree-like appearance in cross-section—are four deep cerebellar nuclei, composed of gray matter.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Connecting the cerebellum to different parts of the nervous system are three paired cerebellar peduncles.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] These are the superior cerebellar peduncle, the middle cerebellar peduncle and the inferior cerebellar peduncle, named by their position relative to the vermis.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The superior cerebellar peduncle is mainly an output to the cerebral cortex, carrying efferent fibers via thalamic nuclei to upper motor neurons in the cerebral cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The fibers arise from the deep cerebellar nuclei.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The middle cerebellar peduncle is connected to the pons and receives all of its input from the pons mainly from the pontine nuclei.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The input to the pons is from the cerebral cortex and is relayed from the pontine nuclei via transverse pontine fibers to the cerebellum.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The middle peduncle is the largest of the three and its afferent fibers are grouped into three separate fascicles taking their inputs to different parts of the cerebellum.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The inferior cerebellar peduncle receives input from afferent fibers from the vestibular nuclei, spinal cord and the tegmentum.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Output from the inferior peduncle is via efferent fibers to the vestibular nuclei and the reticular formation.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The whole of the cerebellum receives modulatory input from the inferior olivary nucleus via the inferior cerebellar peduncle.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Based on the surface appearance, three lobes can be distinguished within the cerebellum: the anterior lobe (above the primary fissure), the posterior lobe (below the primary fissure), and the flocculonodular lobe (below the posterior fissure).
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] These lobes divide the cerebellum from rostral to caudal (in humans, top to bottom).
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] In terms of function, however, there is a more important distinction along the medial-to-lateral dimension.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Leaving out the flocculonodular lobe, which has distinct connections and functions, the cerebellum can be parsed functionally into a medial sector called the spinocerebellum and a larger lateral sector called the cerebrocerebellum.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] A narrow strip of protruding tissue along the midline is called the cerebellar vermis.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The smallest region, the flocculonodular lobe, is often called the vestibulocerebellum.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] It is the oldest part in evolutionary terms (archicerebellum) and participates mainly in balance and spatial orientation; its primary connections are with the vestibular nuclei, although it also receives visual and other sensory input.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Damage to this region causes disturbances of balance and gait.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The medial zone of the anterior and posterior lobes constitutes the spinocerebellum, also known as paleocerebellum.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] This sector of the cerebellum functions mainly to fine-tune body and limb movements.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] It receives proprioceptive input from the dorsal columns of the spinal cord (including the spinocerebellar tract) and from the cranial trigeminal nerve, as well as from visual and auditory systems.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] It sends fibers to deep cerebellar nuclei that, in turn, project to both the cerebral cortex and the brain stem, thus providing modulation of descending motor systems.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The lateral zone, which in humans is by far the largest part, constitutes the cerebrocerebellum, also known as neocerebellum.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Two types of neuron play dominant roles in the cerebellar circuit: Purkinje cells and granule cells.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Three types of axons also play dominant roles: mossy fibers and climbing fibers (which enter the cerebellum from outside), and parallel fibers (which are the axons of granule cells).
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] There are two main pathways through the cerebellar circuit, originating from mossy fibers and climbing fibers, both eventually terminating in the deep cerebellar nuclei.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Mossy fibers project directly to the deep nuclei, but also give rise to the following pathway: mossy fibers → granule cells → parallel fibers → Purkinje cells → deep nuclei.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Climbing fibers project to Purkinje cells and also send collaterals directly to the deep nuclei.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The mossy fiber and climbing fiber inputs each carry fiber-specific information; the cerebellum also receives dopaminergic, serotonergic, noradrenergic, and cholinergic inputs that presumably perform global modulation.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The cerebellar cortex is divided into three layers.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] At the bottom lies the thick granular layer, densely packed with granule cells, along with interneurons, mainly Golgi cells but also including Lugaro cells and unipolar brush cells.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] In the middle lies the Purkinje layer, a narrow zone that contains the cell bodies of Purkinje cells and Bergmann glial cells.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] At the top lies the molecular layer, which contains the flattened dendritic trees of Purkinje cells, along with the huge array of parallel fibers penetrating the Purkinje cell dendritic trees at right angles.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] This outermost layer of the cerebellar cortex also contains two types of inhibitory interneuron: stellate cells and basket cells.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Both stellate and basket cells form GABAergic synapses onto Purkinje cell dendrites.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The top, outermost layer of the cerebellar cortex is the molecular layer.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] This layer contains the flattened dendritic trees of Purkinje cells, and the huge array of parallel fibers, from the granular layer, that penetrate the Purkinje cell dendritic trees at right angles.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The molecular layer also contains two types of inhibitory interneuron: stellate cells and basket cells.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Purkinje cells are among the most distinctive neurons in the brain, and one of the earliest types to be recognized—they were first described by the Czech anatomist Jan Evangelista Purkyně in 1837.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] They are distinguished by the shape of their dendritic tree: the dendrites branch very profusely, but are severely flattened in a plane perpendicular to the cerebellar folds.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Thus, the dendrites of a Purkinje cell form a dense planar net, through which parallel fibers pass at right angles.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The dendrites are covered with dendritic spines, each of which receives synaptic input from a parallel fiber.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Purkinje cells receive more synaptic inputs than any other type of cell in the brain—estimates of the number of spines on a single human Purkinje cell run as high as 200,000.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The large, spherical cell bodies of Purkinje cells are packed into a narrow layer (one cell thick) of the cerebellar cortex, called the *Purkinje layer*.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] After emitting collaterals that affect nearby parts of the cortex, their axons travel into the deep cerebellar nuclei, where they make on the order of 1,000 contacts each with several types of nuclear cells, all within a small domain.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Purkinje cells use GABA as their neurotransmitter, and therefore exert inhibitory effects on their targets.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Purkinje cells form the heart of the cerebellar circuit, and their large size and distinctive activity patterns have made it relatively easy to study their response patterns in behaving animals using extracellular recording techniques.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Purkinje cells normally emit action potentials at a high rate even in the absence of the synaptic input.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] In awake, behaving animals, mean rates averaging around 40 Hz are typical.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The spike trains show a mixture of what are called simple and complex spikes.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] A simple spike is a single action potential followed by a refractory period of about 10 ms; a complex spike is a stereotyped sequence of action potentials with very short inter-spike intervals and declining amplitudes.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Physiological studies have shown that complex spikes (which occur at baseline rates around 1 Hz and never at rates much higher than 10 Hz) are reliably associated with climbing fiber activation, while simple spikes are produced by a combination of baseline activity and parallel fiber input.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Complex spikes are often followed by a pause of several hundred milliseconds during which simple spike activity is suppressed.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] A specific, recognizable feature of Purkinje neurons is the expression of calbindin.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Calbindin staining of rat brain after unilateral chronic sciatic nerve injury suggests that Purkinje neurons may be newly generated in the adult brain, initiating the organization of new cerebellar lobules.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Cerebellar granule cells, in contrast to Purkinje cells, are among the smallest neurons in the brain.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] They are also the most numerous neurons in the brain: In humans, estimates of their total number average around 50 billion, which means that about 3/4 of the brain's neurons are cerebellar granule cells.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Their cell bodies are packed into a thick layer at the bottom of the cerebellar cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] A granule cell emits only four to five dendrites, each of which ends in an enlargement called a *dendritic claw*.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] These enlargements are sites of excitatory input from mossy fibers and inhibitory input from Golgi cells.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] A human parallel fiber runs for an average of 3 mm in each direction from the split, for a total length of about 6 mm (about 1/10 of the total width of the cortical layer).
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] As they run along, the parallel fibers pass through the dendritic trees of Purkinje cells, contacting one of every 3–5 that they pass, making a total of 80–100 synaptic connections with Purkinje cell dendritic spines.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Granule cells use glutamate as their neurotransmitter, and therefore exert excitatory effects on their targets.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Granule cells receive all of their input from mossy fibers, but outnumber them by 200 to 1 (in humans).
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Thus, the information in the granule cell population activity state is the same as the information in the mossy fibers, but recoded in a much more expansive way.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Because granule cells are so small and so densely packed, it is difficult to record their spike activity in behaving animals, so there is little data to use as a basis for theorizing.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The most popular concept of their function was proposed in 1969 by David Marr, who suggested that they could encode combinations of mossy fiber inputs.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The idea is that with each granule cell receiving input from only 4–5 mossy fibers, a granule cell would not respond if only a single one of its inputs were active, but would respond if more than one were active.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] This combinatorial coding scheme would potentially allow the cerebellum to make much finer distinctions between input patterns than the mossy fibers alone would permit.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Mossy fibers enter the granular layer from their points of origin, many arising from the pontine nuclei, others from the spinal cord, vestibular nuclei etc.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] In the human cerebellum, the total number of mossy fibers has been estimated at 200 million.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] These fibers form excitatory synapses with the granule cells and the cells of the deep cerebellar nuclei.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Within the granular layer, a mossy fiber generates a series of enlargements called *rosettes*.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The contacts between mossy fibers and granule cell dendrites take place within structures called glomeruli.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Each glomerulus has a mossy fiber rosette at its center, and up to 20 granule cell dendritic claws contacting it.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Terminals from Golgi cells infiltrate the structure and make inhibitory synapses onto the granule cell dendrites.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The entire assemblage is surrounded by a sheath of glial cells.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Each mossy fiber sends collateral branches to several cerebellar folia, generating a total of 20–30 rosettes; thus a single mossy fiber makes contact with an estimated 400–600 granule cells.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Purkinje cells also receive input from the inferior olivary nucleus on the contralateral side of the brainstem via climbing fibers.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Although the inferior olive lies in the medulla oblongata and receives input from the spinal cord, brainstem and cerebral cortex, its output goes entirely to the cerebellum.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] A climbing fiber gives off collaterals to the deep cerebellar nuclei before entering the cerebellar cortex, where it splits into about 10 terminal branches, each of which gives input to a single Purkinje cell.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] In striking contrast to the 100,000-plus inputs from parallel fibers, each Purkinje cell receives input from exactly one climbing fiber; but this single fiber "climbs" the dendrites of the Purkinje cell, winding around them and making a total of up to 300 synapses as it goes.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The net input is so strong that a single action potential from a climbing fiber is capable of producing an extended complex spike in the Purkinje cell: a burst of several spikes in a row, with diminishing amplitude, followed by a pause during which activity is suppressed.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The climbing fiber synapses cover the cell body and proximal dendrites; this zone is devoid of parallel fiber inputs.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Climbing fibers fire at low rates, but a single climbing fiber action potential induces a burst of several action potentials in a target Purkinje cell (a complex spike).
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The contrast between parallel fiber and climbing fiber inputs to Purkinje cells (over 100,000 of one type versus exactly one of the other type) is perhaps the most provocative feature of cerebellar anatomy, and has motivated much of the theorizing.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] In fact, the function of climbing fibers is the most controversial topic concerning the cerebellum.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] There are two schools of thought, one following Marr and Albus in holding that climbing fiber input serves primarily as a teaching signal, the other holding that its function is to shape cerebellar output directly.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Both views have been defended in great length in numerous publications.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] In the words of one review, "In trying to synthesize the various hypotheses on the function of the climbing fibers, one has the sense of looking at a drawing by Escher.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Each point of view seems to account for a certain collection of findings, but when one attempts to put the different views together, a coherent picture of what the climbing fibers are doing does not appear.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] For the majority of researchers, the climbing fibers signal errors in motor performance, either in the usual manner of discharge frequency modulation or as a single announcement of an 'unexpected event'.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The deep nuclei of the cerebellum are clusters of gray matter lying within the white matter at the core of the cerebellum.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] They are, with the minor exception of the nearby vestibular nuclei, the sole sources of output from the cerebellum.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] These nuclei receive collateral projections from mossy fibers and climbing fibers as well as inhibitory input from the Purkinje cells of the cerebellar cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The four nuclei (dentate, globose, emboliform, and fastigial) each communicate with different parts of the brain and cerebellar cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] (The globose and the emboliform nuclei are also referred to as combined in the interposed nucleus).
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The fastigial and interposed nuclei belong to the spinocerebellum.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The dentate nucleus, which in mammals is much larger than the others, is formed as a thin, convoluted layer of gray matter, and communicates exclusively with the lateral parts of the cerebellar cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The flocculus of the flocculonodular lobe is the only part of the cerebellar cortex that does not project to the deep nuclei—its output goes to the vestibular nuclei instead.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The majority of neurons in the deep nuclei have large cell bodies and spherical dendritic trees with a radius of about 400 μm, and use glutamate as their neurotransmitter.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] These cells project to a variety of targets outside the cerebellum.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Intermixed with them are a lesser number of small cells, which use GABA as a neurotransmitter and project exclusively to the inferior olivary nucleus, the source of climbing fibers.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Thus, the nucleo-olivary projection provides an inhibitory feedback to match the excitatory projection of climbing fibers to the nuclei.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] There is evidence that each small cluster of nuclear cells projects to the same cluster of olivary cells that send climbing fibers to it; there is strong and matching topography in both directions.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] When a Purkinje cell axon enters one of the deep nuclei, it branches to make contact with both large and small nuclear cells, but the total number of cells contacted is only about 35 (in cats).
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Conversely, a single deep nuclear cell receives input from approximately 860 Purkinje cells (again in cats).
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] From the viewpoint of gross anatomy, the cerebellar cortex appears to be a homogeneous sheet of tissue, and, from the viewpoint of microanatomy, all parts of this sheet appear to have the same internal structure.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] There are, however, a number of respects in which the structure of the cerebellum is compartmentalized.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] There are large compartments that are generally known as *zones*; these can be divided into smaller compartments known as *microzones*.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The first indications of compartmental structure came from studies of the receptive fields of cells in various parts of the cerebellar cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Each body part maps to specific points in the cerebellum, but there are numerous repetitions of the basic map, forming an arrangement that has been called "fractured somatotopy".
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] A clearer indication of compartmentalization is obtained by immunostaining the cerebellum for certain types of protein.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The best-known of these markers are called "zebrins", because staining for them gives rise to a complex pattern reminiscent of the stripes on a zebra.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The stripes generated by zebrins and other compartmentalization markers are oriented perpendicular to the cerebellar folds—that is, they are narrow in the mediolateral direction, but much more extended in the longitudinal direction.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Different markers generate different sets of stripes, the widths and lengths vary as a function of location, but they all have the same general shape.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Oscarsson in the late 1970s proposed that these cortical zones can be partitioned into smaller units called microzones.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] A microzone is defined as a group of Purkinje cells all having the same somatotopic receptive field.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Microzones were found to contain on the order of 1000 Purkinje cells each, arranged in a long, narrow strip, oriented perpendicular to the cortical folds.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Thus, as the adjoining diagram illustrates, Purkinje cell dendrites are flattened in the same direction as the microzones extend, while parallel fibers cross them at right angles.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] It is not only receptive fields that define the microzone structure: The climbing fiber input from the inferior olivary nucleus is equally important.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The branches of a climbing fiber (usually numbering about 10) usually activate Purkinje cells belonging to the same microzone.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Moreover, olivary neurons that send climbing fibers to the same microzone tend to be coupled by gap junctions, which synchronize their activity, causing Purkinje cells within a microzone to show correlated complex spike activity on a millisecond time scale.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Also, the Purkinje cells belonging to a microzone all send their axons to the same small cluster of output cells within the deep cerebellar nuclei.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Finally, the axons of basket cells are much longer in the longitudinal direction than in the mediolateral direction, causing them to be confined largely to a single microzone.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The consequence of all this structure is that cellular interactions within a microzone are much stronger than interactions between different microzones.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] In 2005, Richard Apps and Martin Garwicz summarized evidence that microzones themselves form part of a larger entity they call a multizonal microcomplex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Such a microcomplex includes several spatially separated cortical microzones, all of which project to the same group of deep cerebellar neurons, plus a group of coupled olivary neurons that project to all of the included microzones as well as to the deep nuclear area.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The cerebellum is provided with blood from three paired major arteries: the superior cerebellar artery (SCA), the anterior inferior cerebellar artery (AICA), and the posterior inferior cerebellar artery (PICA).
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The SCA supplies the upper region of the cerebellum.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] It divides at the upper surface and branches into the pia mater where the branches anastomose with those of the anterior and posterior inferior cerebellar arteries.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The AICA supplies the front part of the undersurface of the cerebellum.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The PICA arrives at the undersurface, where it divides into a medial branch and a lateral branch.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The medial branch continues backward to the cerebellar notch between the two hemispheres of the cerebellum; while the lateral branch supplies the under surface of the cerebellum, as far as its lateral border, where it anastomoses with the AICA and the SCA.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The strongest clues to the function of the cerebellum have come from examining the consequences of damage to it.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Animals and humans with cerebellar dysfunction show, above all, problems with motor control, on the same side of the body as the damaged part of the cerebellum.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] They continue to be able to generate motor activity but lose precision, producing erratic, uncoordinated, or incorrectly timed movements.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] A standard test of cerebellar function is to reach with the tip of the finger for a target at arm's length: A healthy person will move the fingertip in a rapid straight trajectory, whereas a person with cerebellar damage will reach slowly and erratically, with many mid-course corrections.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Deficits in non-motor functions are more difficult to detect.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Thus, the general conclusion reached decades ago is that the basic function of the cerebellum is to calibrate the detailed form of a movement, not to initiate movements or to decide which movements to execute.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Prior to the 1990s the function of the cerebellum was mostly believed to be purely motor-related, but later research has pointed to an expanded role of cerebellar connectivity beyond basic motoric functions.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] In particular, the cerebellar cognitive affective syndrome or Schmahmann's syndrome has been described in adults and children.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Estimates based on functional mapping of the cerebellum using functional MRI suggest that more than half of the cerebellar cortex is interconnected with association zones of the cerebral cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] If the input and output connections of a module are with motor areas (as many are), then the module will be involved in motor behavior; but, if the connections are with areas involved in non-motor cognition, the module will show other types of behavioral correlates.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Thus the cerebellum has been implicated in the regulation of many differing functional traits such as affection, emotion including emotional body language perception and behavior.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The cerebellum, Doya proposes, is best understood as predictive action selection based on "internal models" of the environment or a device for supervised learning, in contrast to the basal ganglia, which perform reinforcement learning, and the cerebral cortex, which performs unsupervised learning.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Three decades of brain research have led to the proposal that the cerebellum generates optimized mental models and interacts closely with the cerebral cortex, where updated internal models are experienced as creative intuition ("a ha") in working memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The comparative simplicity and regularity of the cerebellar anatomy led to an early hope that it might imply a similar simplicity of computational function, as expressed in one of the first books on cerebellar electrophysiology, *The Cerebellum as a Neuronal Machine* by John C.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Eccles, Masao Ito, and János Szentágothai.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Although a full understanding of cerebellar function has remained elusive, at least four principles have been identified as important: (1) feedforward processing, (2) divergence and convergence, (3) modularity, and (4) plasticity.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] **Divergence and convergence**: In the human cerebellum, information from 200 million mossy fiber inputs is expanded to 40 billion granule cells, whose parallel fiber outputs then converge onto 15 million Purkinje cells.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Because of the way that they are lined up longitudinally, the 1000 or so Purkinje cells belonging to a microzone may receive input from as many as 100 million parallel fibers, and focus their own output down to a group of fewer still deep nuclear cells.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Thus, the cerebellar network receives a modest number of inputs, processes them very extensively through its rigorously structured internal network, and sends out the results via a very limited number of output cells.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] **Modularity**: The cerebellar system is functionally divided into more or less independent modules, which probably number in the hundreds to thousands.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] All modules have a similar internal structure, but different inputs and outputs.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Different modules share input from mossy fibers and parallel fibers, but in other respects they appear to function independently—the output of one module does not appear to significantly influence the activity of other modules.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] **Plasticity**: The synapses between parallel fibers and Purkinje cells, and the synapses between mossy fibers and deep nuclear cells, are both susceptible to modification of their strength.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] In a single cerebellar module, input from as many as a billion parallel fibers converges onto a group of less than 50 deep nuclear cells, and the influence of each parallel fiber on those nuclear cells is adjustable.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] This arrangement gives tremendous flexibility for fine-tuning the relationship between the cerebellar inputs and outputs.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] There is considerable evidence that the cerebellum plays an essential role in some types of motor learning.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The tasks where the cerebellum most clearly comes into play are those in which it is necessary to make fine adjustments to the way an action is performed.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] There has, however, been much dispute about whether learning takes place within the cerebellum itself, or whether it merely serves to provide signals that promote learning in other brain structures.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Most theories that assign learning to the circuitry of the cerebellum are derived from the ideas of David Marr and James Albus, who postulated that climbing fibers provide a teaching signal that induces synaptic modification in parallel fiber–Purkinje cell synapses.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Marr assumed that climbing fiber input would cause synchronously activated parallel fiber inputs to be strengthened.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Most subsequent cerebellar-learning models, however, have followed Albus in assuming that climbing fiber activity would be an error signal, and would cause synchronously activated parallel fiber inputs to be weakened.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Some of these later models, such as the *Adaptive Filter* model of Fujita made attempts to understand cerebellar function in terms of optimal control theory.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The idea that climbing fiber activity functions as an error signal has been examined in many experimental studies, with some supporting it but others casting doubt.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] In a pioneering study by Gilbert and Thach from 1977, Purkinje cells from monkeys learning a reaching task showed increased complex spike activity—which is known to reliably indicate activity of the cell's climbing fiber input—during periods when performance was poor.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Several studies of motor learning in cats observed complex spike activity when there was a mismatch between an intended movement and the movement that was actually executed.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Studies of the vestibulo-ocular reflex (which stabilizes the visual image on the retina when the head turns) found that climbing fiber activity indicated "retinal slip", although not in a very straightforward way.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] One of the most extensively studied cerebellar learning tasks is the eyeblink conditioning paradigm, in which a neutral conditioned stimulus (CS) such as a tone or a light is repeatedly paired with an unconditioned stimulus (US), such as an air puff, that elicits a blink response.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] After such repeated presentations of the CS and US, the CS will eventually elicit a blink before the US, a conditioned response or CR.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Experiments showed that lesions localized either to a specific part of the interposed nucleus (one of the deep cerebellar nuclei) or to a few specific points in the cerebellar cortex would abolish learning of a conditionally timed blink response.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The large base of knowledge about the anatomical structure and behavioral functions of the cerebellum have made it a fertile ground for theorizing—there are perhaps more theories of the function of the cerebellum than of any other part of the brain.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Several theories of both types have been formulated as mathematical models and simulated using computers.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] A Kalman filter model has been proposed that fits with two major requirements: the cerebellum as involved in predictions and in sequencing.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Perhaps the earliest "performance" theory was the "delay line" hypothesis of Valentino Braitenberg.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The original theory put forth by Braitenberg and Roger Atwood in 1958 proposed that slow propagation of signals along parallel fibers imposes predictable delays that allow the cerebellum to detect time relationships within a certain window.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Experimental data did not support the original form of the theory, but Braitenberg continued to argue for modified versions.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The hypothesis that the cerebellum functions essentially as a timing system has also been advocated by Richard Ivry.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Another influential "performance" theory is the Tensor network theory of Pellionisz and Llinás, which provided an advanced mathematical formulation of the idea that the fundamental computation performed by the cerebellum is to transform sensory into motor coordinates.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Theories in the "learning" category almost all derive from publications by Marr and Albus.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Marr's 1969 paper proposed that the cerebellum is a device for learning to associate elemental movements encoded by climbing fibers with mossy fiber inputs that encode the sensory context.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Albus proposed in 1971 that a cerebellar Purkinje cell functions as a perceptron, a neurally inspired abstract learning device.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The most basic difference between the Marr and Albus theories is that Marr assumed that climbing fiber activity would cause parallel fiber synapses to be strengthened, whereas Albus proposed that they would be weakened.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Albus also formulated his version as a software algorithm he called a CMAC (Cerebellar Model Articulation Controller), which has been tested in a number of applications.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The lower trace shows an attempt by a patient with cerebellar disease to reproduce the upper trace.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Damage to the cerebellum often causes motor-related symptoms, the details of which depend on the part of the cerebellum involved and how it is damaged.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Damage to the flocculonodular lobe may show up as a loss of equilibrium and in particular an altered, irregular walking gait, with a wide stance caused by difficulty in balancing.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Damage to the lateral zone typically causes problems in skilled voluntary and planned movements which can cause errors in the force, direction, speed and amplitude of movements.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Damage to the midline portion may disrupt whole-body movements, whereas damage localized more laterally is more likely to disrupt fine movements of the hands or limbs.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Damage to the upper part of the cerebellum tends to cause gait impairments and other problems with leg coordination; damage to the lower part is more likely to cause uncoordinated or poorly aimed movements of the arms and hands, as well as difficulties in speed.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] This complex of motor symptoms is called *ataxia*.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] To identify cerebellar problems, neurological examination includes assessment of gait (a broad-based gait being indicative of ataxia), finger-pointing tests and assessment of posture.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] If cerebellar dysfunction is indicated, a magnetic resonance imaging scan can be used to obtain a detailed picture of any structural alterations that may exist.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The list of medical problems that can produce cerebellar damage is long, including stroke, hemorrhage, swelling of the brain (cerebral edema), tumors, alcoholism, physical trauma such as gunshot wounds or explosives, and chronic degenerative conditions such as olivopontocerebellar atrophy.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Some forms of migraine headache may also produce temporary dysfunction of the cerebellum, of variable severity.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Infection can result in cerebellar damage in such conditions as the prion diseases and Miller Fisher syndrome, a variant of Guillain–Barré syndrome.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] These changes may differ from those of other parts of the brain.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The cerebellum is the youngest brain region (and body part) according to an epigenetic biomarker of tissue age known as an epigenetic clock: it is about 15 years younger than expected in a centenarian.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Further, gene expression patterns in the human cerebellum show less age-related alteration than that in the cerebral cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Some studies have reported reductions in numbers of cells or volume of tissue, but the amount of data relating to this question is not very large.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Congenital malformation, hereditary disorders, and acquired conditions can affect cerebellar structure and, consequently, cerebellar function.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Unless the causative condition is reversible, the only possible treatment is to help people live with their problems.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Visualization of the fetal cerebellum by ultrasound scan at 18 to 20 weeks of pregnancy can be used to screen for fetal neural tube defects with a sensitivity rate of up to 99%.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] In normal development, endogenous sonic hedgehog signaling stimulates rapid proliferation of cerebellar granule neuron progenitors (CGNPs) in the external granule layer (EGL).
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Cerebellar development occurs during late embryogenesis and the early postnatal period, with CGNP proliferation in the EGL peaking during early development (postnatal day 7 in the mouse).
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] As CGNPs terminally differentiate into cerebellar granule cells (also called cerebellar granule neurons, CGNs), they migrate to the internal granule layer (IGL), forming the mature cerebellum (by post-natal day 20 in the mouse).
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Mutations that abnormally activate sonic hedgehog signaling predispose to cancer of the cerebellum (medulloblastoma) in humans with Gorlin Syndrome and in genetically engineered mouse models.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Congenital malformation or underdevelopment (hypoplasia) of the cerebellar vermis is a characteristic of both Dandy–Walker syndrome and Joubert syndrome.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] In very rare cases, the entire cerebellum may be absent.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The inherited neurological disorders Machado–Joseph disease, ataxia telangiectasia, and Friedreich's ataxia cause progressive neurodegeneration linked to cerebellar loss.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Congenital brain malformations outside the cerebellum can, in turn, cause herniation of cerebellar tissue, as seen in some forms of Arnold–Chiari malformation.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Cerebellar atrophy can result from chronic thiamine (vitamin B1) deficiency as seen in dry beriberi and in Wernicke–Korsakoff syndrome, or from vitamin E deficiency.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Cerebellar atrophy has been observed in many other neurological disorders including Huntington's disease, multiple sclerosis, essential tremor, progressive myoclonus epilepsy, and Niemann–Pick disease.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Cerebellar atrophy can also occur as a result of exposure to toxins including heavy metals or pharmaceutical or recreational drugs.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] There is a general consensus that the cerebellum is involved in pain processing.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The cerebellum receives pain input from both descending cortico-cerebellar pathways and ascending spino-cerebellar pathways, through the pontine nuclei and inferior olives.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] Some of this information is transferred to the motor system inducing a conscious motor avoidance of pain, graded according to pain intensity.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] These direct pain inputs, as well as indirect inputs, are thought to induce long-term pain avoidance behavior that results in chronic posture changes and consequently, in functional and anatomical remodeling of vestibular and proprioceptive nuclei.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] As a result, chronic neuropathic pain can induce macroscopic anatomical remodeling of the hindbrain, including the cerebellum.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p01] The magnitude of this remodeling and the induction of neuron progenitor markers suggest the contribution of adult neurogenesis to these changes.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] The circuits in the cerebellum are similar across all classes of vertebrates, including fish, reptiles, birds, and mammals.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] There is also an analogous brain structure in cephalopods with well-developed brains, such as octopuses.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] This has been taken as evidence that the cerebellum performs functions important to all animal species with a brain.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] There is considerable variation in the size and shape of the cerebellum in different vertebrate species.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] In amphibians, it is little developed, and in lampreys, and hagfish, the cerebellum is barely distinguishable from the brain-stem.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] Although the spinocerebellum is present in these groups, the primary structures are small, paired-nuclei corresponding to the vestibulocerebellum.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] The cerebellum is a bit larger in reptiles, considerably larger in birds, and larger still in mammals.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] The large paired and convoluted lobes found in humans are typical of mammals, but the cerebellum is, in general, a single median lobe in other groups, and is either smooth or only slightly grooved.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] In mammals, the neocerebellum is the major part of the cerebellum by mass, but, in other vertebrates, it is typically the spinocerebellum.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] The cerebellum of cartilaginous and bony fishes is extraordinarily large and complex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] In at least one important respect, it differs in internal structure from the mammalian cerebellum: The fish cerebellum does not contain discrete deep cerebellar nuclei.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] Instead, the primary targets of Purkinje cells are a distinct type of cell distributed across the cerebellar cortex, a type not seen in mammals.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] In mormyrid fish (a family of weakly electrosensitive freshwater fish), the cerebellum is considerably larger than the rest of the brain.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] The largest part of it is a special structure called the *valvula*, which has an unusually regular architecture and receives much of its input from the electrosensory system.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] The hallmark of the mammalian cerebellum is an expansion of the lateral lobes, whose main interactions are with the neocortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] As monkeys evolved into great apes, the expansion of the lateral lobes continued, in tandem with the expansion of the frontal lobes of the neocortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] In ancestral hominids, and in *Homo sapiens* until the middle Pleistocene period, the cerebellum continued to expand, but the frontal lobes expanded more rapidly.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] The most recent period of human evolution, however, may actually have been associated with an increase in the relative size of the cerebellum, as the neocortex reduced its size somewhat while the cerebellum expanded.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] The size of the human cerebellum, compared to the rest of the brain, has been increasing in size while the cerebrum decreased in size.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] With both the development and implementation of motor tasks, visual-spatial skills and learning taking place in the cerebellum, the growth of the cerebellum is thought to have some form of correlation to greater human cognitive abilities.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] The lateral hemispheres of the cerebellum are now 2.7 times greater in both humans and apes than they are in monkeys.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] These changes in the cerebellum size cannot be explained by greater muscle mass.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] They show that either the development of the cerebellum is tightly linked to that of the rest of the brain or that neural activities taking place in the cerebellum were important during Hominidae evolution.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] Due to the cerebellum's role in cognitive functions, the increase in its size may have played a role in cognitive expansion.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] Most vertebrate species have a cerebellum and one or more cerebellum-like structures, brain areas that resemble the cerebellum in terms of cytoarchitecture and neurochemistry.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] The only cerebellum-like structure found in mammals is the dorsal cochlear nucleus (DCN), one of the two primary sensory nuclei that receive input directly from the auditory nerve.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] The DCN is a layered structure, with the bottom layer containing granule cells similar to those of the cerebellum, giving rise to parallel fibers that rise to the superficial layer and travel across it horizontally.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] The superficial layer contains a set of GABAergic neurons called cartwheel cells that resemble Purkinje cells anatomically and chemically—they receive parallel fiber input, but do not have any inputs that resemble climbing fibers.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] The output neurons of the DCN are pyramidal cells.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] The DCN is most highly developed in rodents and other small animals, and is considerably reduced in primates.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] Its function is not well understood; the most popular speculations relate it to spatial hearing in one way or another.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] Most species of fish and amphibians possess a lateral line system that senses pressure waves in water.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] One of the brain areas that receives primary input from the lateral line organ, the medial octavolateral nucleus, has a cerebellum-like structure, with granule cells and parallel fibers.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] In electrosensitive fish, the input from the electrosensory system goes to the dorsal octavolateral nucleus, which also has a cerebellum-like structure.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] In ray-finned fishes (by far the largest group), the optic tectum has a layer—the marginal layer—that is cerebellum-like.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] All of these cerebellum-like structures appear to be primarily sensory-related rather than motor-related.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] All of them have granule cells that give rise to parallel fibers that connect to Purkinje-like neurons with modifiable synapses, but none have climbing fibers comparable to those of the cerebellum—instead they receive direct input from peripheral sensory organs.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] None has a demonstrated function, but the most influential speculation is that they serve to transform sensory inputs in some sophisticated way, perhaps to compensate for changes in body posture.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] Bower and others have argued, partly on the basis of these structures and partly on the basis of cerebellar studies, that the cerebellum itself is fundamentally a sensory structure, and that it contributes to motor control by moving the body in a way that controls the resulting sensory signals.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] Despite Bower's viewpoint, there is also strong evidence that the cerebellum directly influences motor output in mammals.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] Even the earliest anatomists were able to recognize the cerebellum by its distinctive appearance.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] Aristotle and Herophilus (quoted in Galen) called it the παρεγκεφαλίς (*parenkephalis*), as opposed to the ἐγκέφαλος (*enkephalos*) or brain proper.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] Galen's extensive description is the earliest that survives.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] He speculated that the cerebellum was the source of motor nerves.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] Further significant developments did not come until the Renaissance.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] Vesalius discussed the cerebellum briefly, and the anatomy was described more thoroughly by Thomas Willis in 1664.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] More anatomical work was done during the 18th century, but it was not until early in the 19th century that the first insights into the function of the cerebellum were obtained.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] Luigi Rolando in 1809 established the key finding that damage to the cerebellum results in motor disturbances.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] By the beginning of the 20th century, it was widely accepted that the primary function of the cerebellum relates to motor control; the first half of the 20th century produced several detailed descriptions of the clinical symptoms associated with cerebellar disease in humans.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] The name *cerebellum* is a diminutive of *cerebrum* (brain); it can be translated literally as *little brain*.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] The Latin name is a direct translation of the Ancient Greek παρεγκεφαλίς (*parenkephalis*), which was used in the works of Aristotle, the first known writer to describe the structure.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebellum-p02] No other name is used in the English-language literature, but historically a variety of Greek or Latin-derived names have been used, including *cerebrum parvum*, *encephalion*, *encranion*, *cerebrum posterius*, and *parencephalis*.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The **cerebral cortex**, also known as the **cerebral mantle**, is the outer layer of neural tissue of the cerebrum of the brain in humans and other mammals.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] It is the largest site of neural integration in the central nervous system, and plays a key role in attention, perception, awareness, thought, memory, language, and consciousness.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The six-layered neocortex makes up approximately 90% of the cortex, with the allocortex making up the remainder.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The cortex is divided into left and right parts by the longitudinal fissure, which separates the two cerebral hemispheres that are joined beneath the cortex by the corpus callosum and other commissural fibers.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] In most mammals, apart from small mammals that have small brains, the cerebral cortex is folded, providing a greater surface area in the confined volume of the cranium.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Apart from minimising brain and cranial volume, cortical folding is crucial for the brain circuitry and its functional organisation.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] In mammals with small brains, there is no folding and the cortex is smooth.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] A fold or ridge in the cortex is termed a gyrus (plural gyri) and a groove is termed a sulcus (plural sulci).
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] These surface convolutions appear during fetal development and continue to mature after birth through the process of gyrification.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] In the human brain, the majority of the cerebral cortex is not visible from the outside, but buried in the sulci.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The major sulci and gyri mark the divisions of the cerebrum into the lobes of the brain.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The four major lobes are the frontal, parietal, occipital and temporal lobes.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Other lobes are the limbic lobe, and the insular cortex often referred to as the *insular lobe*.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] There are between 14 and 16 billion neurons in the human cerebral cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] These are organised into horizontal cortical layers, and radially into cortical columns and minicolumns.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Cortical areas have specific functions such as movement in the motor cortex, and sight in the visual cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The motor cortex is primarily located in the precentral gyrus, and the visual cortex is located in the occipital lobe.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The cerebral cortex is the outer covering of the surfaces of the cerebral hemispheres and is folded into peaks called gyri, and grooves called sulci.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] In the human brain, it is between 2 and 3-4 mm. thick, and makes up 40% of the brain's mass.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] 90% of the cerebral cortex is the six-layered neocortex whilst the other 10% is made up of the three/four-layered allocortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] There are between 14 and 16 billion neurons in the cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] These cortical neurons are organized radially in cortical columns, and minicolumns, in the horizontally organized layers of the cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The neocortex is separable into different regions of cortex known in the plural as cortices, and include the motor cortex and visual cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] About two thirds of the cortical surface is buried in the sulci and the insular cortex is completely hidden.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The cortex is thickest over the top of a gyrus and thinnest at the bottom of a sulcus.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The cerebral cortex is folded in a way that allows a large surface area of neural tissue to fit within the confines of the neurocranium.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] When unfolded in the human, each hemispheric cortex has a total surface area of about 0.12 square metres (1.3 sq ft).
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The folding is inward away from the surface of the brain, and is also present on the medial surface of each hemisphere within the longitudinal fissure.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Most mammals have a cerebral cortex that is convoluted with the peaks known as gyri and the troughs or grooves known as sulci.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Some small mammals including some small rodents have smooth cerebral surfaces without gyrification.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The larger sulci and gyri mark the divisions of the cortex of the cerebrum into the lobes of the brain.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] There are four main lobes: the frontal lobe, parietal lobe, temporal lobe, and occipital lobe.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The insular cortex is often included as the insular lobe.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The limbic lobe is a rim of cortex on the medial side of each hemisphere and is also often included.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] There are also three lobules of the brain described: the paracentral lobule, the superior parietal lobule, and the inferior parietal lobule.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] For species of mammals, larger brains (in absolute terms, not just in relation to body size) tend to have thicker cortices.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The smallest mammals, such as shrews, have a neocortical thickness of about 0.5 mm; the ones with the largest brains, such as humans and fin whales, have thicknesses of 2–4 mm.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] There is an approximately logarithmic relationship between brain weight and cortical thickness.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Magnetic resonance imaging of the brain (MRI) makes it possible to get a measure for the thickness of the human cerebral cortex and relate it to other measures.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The thickness of different cortical areas varies but in general, sensory cortex is thinner than motor cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] One study has found some positive association between the cortical thickness and intelligence.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Another study has found that the somatosensory cortex is thicker in migraine patients, though it is not known if this is the result of migraine attacks, the cause of them or if both are the result of a shared cause.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] A later study using a larger patient population reports no change in the cortical thickness in patients with migraine.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] A genetic disorder of the cerebral cortex, whereby decreased folding in certain areas results in a microgyrus, where there are four layers instead of six, is in some instances seen to be related to dyslexia.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The neocortex is formed of six layers, numbered I to VI, from the outermost layer I – near to the pia mater, to the innermost layer VI – near to the underlying white matter.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Each cortical layer has a characteristic distribution of different neurons and their connections with other cortical and subcortical regions.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] There are direct connections between different cortical areas and indirect connections via the thalamus.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] One of the clearest examples of cortical layering is the line of Gennari in the primary visual cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] This is a band of whiter tissue that can be observed with the naked eye in the calcarine sulcus of the occipital lobe.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The line of Gennari is composed of axons bringing visual information from the thalamus into layer IV of the visual cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Staining cross-sections of the cortex to reveal the position of neuronal cell bodies and the intracortical axon tracts allowed neuroanatomists in the early 20th century to produce a detailed description of the *laminar structure of the cortex* in different species.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The work of Korbinian Brodmann (1909) established that the mammalian neocortex is consistently divided into six layers.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Layer I is the **molecular layer**, and contains few scattered neurons, including GABAergic rosehip neurons.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Layer I consists largely of extensions of apical dendritic tufts of pyramidal neurons and horizontally oriented axons, as well as glial cells.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] During development, Cajal–Retzius cells and subpial granular layer cells are present in this layer.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Also, some spiny stellate cells can be found here.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Inputs to the apical tufts are thought to be crucial for the *feedback* interactions in the cerebral cortex involved in associative learning and attention.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] While it was once thought that the input to layer I came from the cortex itself, it is now known that layer I across the cerebral cortex receives substantial input from *matrix* or M-type thalamus cells, as opposed to *core* or C-type that go to layer IV.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] It is thought that layer I serves as a central hub for collecting and processing widespread information.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] It integrates ascending sensory inputs with top-down expectations, regulating how sensory perceptions align with anticipated outcomes.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Further, layer I sorts, directs, and combines excitatory inputs, integrating them with neuromodulatory signals.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Inhibitory interneurons, both within layer I and from other cortical layers, gate these signals.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Together, these interactions dynamically calibrate information flow throughout the neocortex, shaping perceptions and experiences.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Layer II, the **external granular layer**, contains small pyramidal neurons and numerous stellate neurons.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Layer IV, the **internal granular layer**, contains different types of stellate and pyramidal cells, and is the main target of thalamocortical afferents from thalamus type C neurons (core-type) as well as intra-hemispheric corticocortical afferents.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The layers above layer IV are also referred to as supragranular layers (layers I-III), whereas the layers below are referred to as infragranular layers (layers V and VI).
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] African elephants, cetaceans, and hippopotamus do not have a layer IV with axons which would terminate there going instead to the inner part of layer III.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Layer V, the **internal pyramidal layer**, contains large pyramidal neurons.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Axons from these leave the cortex and connect with subcortical structures including the basal ganglia.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] In the primary motor cortex of the frontal lobe, layer V contains giant pyramidal cells called Betz cells, whose axons travel through the internal capsule, the brain stem, and the spinal cord forming the corticospinal tract, which is the main pathway for voluntary motor control.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Layer VI, the **polymorphic layer** or **multiform layer**, contains few large pyramidal neurons and many small spindle-like pyramidal and multiform neurons; layer VI sends efferent fibers to the thalamus, establishing a very precise reciprocal interconnection between the cortex and the thalamus.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] That is, layer VI neurons from one cortical column connect with thalamus neurons that provide input to the same cortical column.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] These connections are both excitatory and inhibitory.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Neurons send excitatory fibers to neurons in the thalamus and also send collaterals to the thalamic reticular nucleus that inhibit these same thalamus neurons or ones adjacent to them.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] One theory is that because the inhibitory output is reduced by cholinergic input to the cerebral cortex, this provides the brainstem with adjustable "gain control for the relay of lemniscal inputs".
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The cortical layers are not simply stacked one over the other; there exist characteristic connections between different layers and neuronal types, which span all the thickness of the cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] These cortical microcircuits are grouped into cortical columns and minicolumns.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] It has been proposed that the minicolumns are the basic functional units of the cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] In 1957, Vernon Mountcastle showed that the functional properties of the cortex change abruptly between laterally adjacent points; however, they are continuous in the direction perpendicular to the surface.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Later works have provided evidence of the presence of functionally distinct cortical columns in the visual cortex (Hubel and Wiesel, 1959), auditory cortex, and associative cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Cortical areas that lack a layer IV are called agranular.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Cortical areas that have only a rudimentary layer IV are called dysgranular.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Information processing within each layer is determined by different temporal dynamics with that in layers II/III having a slow 2 Hz oscillation while that in layer V has a fast 10–15 Hz oscillation.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] There is a transitional area between the neocortex and the allocortex called the paralimbic cortex, where layers 2, 3 and 4 are merged.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] This area incorporates the proisocortex of the neocortex and the periallocortex of the allocortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] In addition, the cerebral cortex may be classified into four lobes: the frontal lobe, temporal lobe, the parietal lobe, and the occipital lobe, named from their overlying bones of the skull.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Blood supply to the cerebral cortex is part of the cerebral circulation.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Cerebral arteries supply the blood that perfuses the cerebrum.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] This arterial blood carries oxygen, glucose, and other nutrients to the cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Cerebral veins drain the deoxygenated blood, and metabolic wastes including carbon dioxide, back to the heart.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The main arteries supplying the cortex are the anterior cerebral artery, the middle cerebral artery, and the posterior cerebral artery.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The anterior cerebral artery supplies the anterior portions of the brain, including most of the frontal lobe.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The middle cerebral artery supplies the parietal lobes, temporal lobes, and parts of the occipital lobes.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The middle cerebral artery splits into two branches to supply the left and right hemisphere, where they branch further.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The posterior cerebral artery supplies the occipital lobes.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The circle of Willis is the main blood system that deals with blood supply in the cerebrum and cerebral cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The prenatal development of the cerebral cortex is a complex and finely tuned process called corticogenesis, influenced by the interplay between genes and the environment.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The cerebral cortex develops from the most anterior part, the forebrain region, of the neural tube.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The neural plate folds and closes to form the neural tube.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] From the cavity inside the neural tube develops the ventricular system, and, from the neuroepithelial cells of its walls, the neurons and glia of the nervous system.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The most anterior (front, or cranial) part of the neural plate, the prosencephalon, which is evident before neurulation begins, gives rise to the cerebral hemispheres and later cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Cortical neurons are generated within the ventricular zone, next to the ventricles.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] At first, this zone contains neural stem cells, that transition to radial glial cells–progenitor cells, which divide to produce glial cells and neurons.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The cerebral cortex is composed of a heterogenous population of cells that give rise to different cell types.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The majority of these cells are derived from radial glia migration that form the different cell types of the neocortex and it is a period associated with an increase in neurogenesis.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Similarly, the process of neurogenesis regulates lamination to form the different layers of the cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] During this process there is an increase in the restriction of cell fate that begins with earlier progenitors giving rise to any cell type in the cortex and later progenitors giving rise only to neurons of superficial layers.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] This differential cell fate creates an inside-out topography in the cortex with younger neurons in superficial layers and older neurons in deeper layers.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] In addition, laminar neurons are stopped in S or G2 phase in order to give a fine distinction between the different cortical layers.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Laminar differentiation is not fully complete until after birth since during development laminar neurons are still sensitive to extrinsic signals and environmental cues.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Although the majority of the cells that compose the cortex are derived locally from radial glia there is a subset population of neurons that migrate from other regions.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Radial glia give rise to neurons that are pyramidal in shape and use glutamate as a neurotransmitter, however these migrating cells contribute neurons that are stellate-shaped and use GABA as their main neurotransmitter.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] These GABAergic neurons are generated by progenitor cells in the medial ganglionic eminence (MGE) that migrate tangentially to the cortex via the subventricular zone.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] This migration of GABAergic neurons is particularly important since GABA receptors are excitatory during development.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] This excitation is primarily driven by the flux of chloride ions through the GABA receptor, however in adults chloride concentrations shift causing an inward flux of chloride that hyperpolarizes postsynaptic neurons.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The glial fibers produced in the first divisions of the progenitor cells are radially oriented, spanning the thickness of the cortex from the ventricular zone to the outer, pial surface, and provide scaffolding for the migration of neurons outwards from the ventricular zone.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] At birth there are very few dendrites present on the cortical neuron's cell body, and the axon is undeveloped.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] During the first year of life the dendrites become dramatically increased in number, such that they can accommodate up to a hundred thousand synaptic connections with other neurons.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The axon can develop to extend a long way from the cell body.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The first divisions of the progenitor cells are symmetric, which duplicates the total number of progenitor cells at each mitotic cycle.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] As the G1 phase of mitosis is elongated, in what is seen as selective cell-cycle lengthening, the newly born neurons migrate to more superficial layers of the cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The migrating daughter cells become the pyramidal cells of the cerebral cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The development process is time ordered and regulated by hundreds of genes and epigenetic regulatory mechanisms.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The layered structure of the mature cerebral cortex is formed during development.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The first pyramidal neurons generated migrate out of the ventricular zone and subventricular zone, together with reelin-producing Cajal–Retzius neurons, from the **preplate**.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Next, a cohort of neurons migrating into the middle of the preplate divides this transient layer into the superficial **marginal zone**, which will become layer I of the mature neocortex, and the subplate, forming a middle layer called the **cortical plate**.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] These cells will form the deep layers of the mature cortex, layers five and six.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Later born neurons migrate radially into the cortical plate past the deep layer neurons, and become the upper layers (two to four).
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Thus, the layers of the cortex are created in an inside-out order.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The only exception to this inside-out sequence of neurogenesis occurs in the layer I of primates, in which, in contrast to rodents, neurogenesis continues throughout the entire period of corticogenesis.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The map of functional cortical areas, which include primary motor and visual cortex, originates from a 'protomap', which is regulated by molecular signals such as fibroblast growth factor FGF8 early in embryonic development.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] These signals regulate the size, shape, and position of cortical areas on the surface of the cortical primordium, in part by regulating gradients of transcription factor expression, through a process called cortical patterning.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Examples of such transcription factors include the genes EMX2 and PAX6.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Together, both transcription factors form an opposing gradient of expression.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Pax6 is highly expressed at the rostral lateral pole, while Emx2 is highly expressed in the caudomedial pole.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The establishment of this gradient is important for proper development.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] For example, mutations in Pax6 can cause expression levels of Emx2 to expand out of its normal expression domain, which would ultimately lead to an expansion of the areas normally derived from the caudal medial cortex, such as the visual cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] On the contrary, if mutations in Emx2 occur, it can cause the Pax6-expressing domain to expand and result in the frontal and motor cortical regions enlarging.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Therefore, researchers believe that similar gradients and signaling centers next to the cortex could contribute to the regional expression of these transcription factors.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Two very well studied patterning signals for the cortex include FGF and retinoic acid.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] If FGFs are misexpressed in different areas of the developing cortex, cortical patterning is disrupted.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Specifically, when Fgf8 is increased in the anterior pole, Emx2 is downregulated and a caudal shift in the cortical region occurs.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] This ultimately causes an expansion of the rostral regions.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Therefore, Fgf8 and other FGFs play a role in the regulation of expression of Emx2 and Pax6 and represent how the cerebral cortex can become specialized for different functions.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Rapid expansion of the cortical surface area is regulated by the amount of self-renewal of radial glial cells and is partly regulated by FGF and Notch genes.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] During the period of cortical neurogenesis and layer formation, many higher mammals begin the process of gyrification, which generates the characteristic folds of the cerebral cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Gyrification is regulated by a DNA-associated protein Trnp1 and by FGF and SHH signaling.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Of all the different brain regions, the cerebral cortex shows the largest evolutionary variation and has evolved most recently.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] In contrast to the highly conserved circuitry of the medulla oblongata, for example, which serves critical functions such as regulation of heart and respiration rates, many areas of the cerebral cortex are not strictly necessary for survival.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Thus, the evolution of the cerebral cortex has seen the advent and modification of new functional areas—particularly association areas that do not directly receive input from outside the cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] A key theory of cortical evolution is embodied in the radial unit hypothesis and related protomap hypothesis, first proposed by Rakic.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] This theory states that new cortical areas are formed by the addition of new radial units, which is accomplished at the stem cell level.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The protomap hypothesis states that the cellular and molecular identity and characteristics of neurons in each cortical area are specified by cortical stem cells, known as radial glial cells, in a primordial map.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] This map is controlled by secreted signaling proteins and downstream transcription factors.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The cerebral cortex is connected to various subcortical structures such as the thalamus and the basal ganglia, sending information to them along efferent connections and receiving information from them via afferent connections.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Most sensory information is routed to the cerebral cortex via the thalamus.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Olfactory information, however, passes through the olfactory bulb to the olfactory cortex (piriform cortex).
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The whole of the cerebral cortex was divided into 52 different areas in an early presentation by Korbinian Brodmann.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] These areas, known as Brodmann areas, are based on their cytoarchitecture but also relate to various functions.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] An example is Brodmann area 17, which is the primary visual cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] In more general terms the cortex is typically described as comprising three parts: sensory, motor, and association areas.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Sensory and motor areas are defined as primary regions, while association areas work with primary regions but go beyond them.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The sensory areas are the cortical areas that receive and process information from the senses.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Parts of the cortex that receive sensory inputs from the thalamus are called primary sensory areas.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The senses of vision, hearing, and touch are served by the primary visual cortex, primary auditory cortex and primary somatosensory cortex respectively.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] In general, the two hemispheres receive information from the opposite (contralateral) side of the body.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] For example, the right primary somatosensory cortex receives information from the left limbs, and the right visual cortex receives information from the left visual field.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The organization of sensory maps in the cortex reflects that of the corresponding sensing organ, in what is known as a topographic map.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Neighboring points in the primary visual cortex, for example, correspond to neighboring points in the retina.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] This topographic map is called a retinotopic map.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] In the same way, there exists a tonotopic map in the primary auditory cortex and a somatotopic map in the primary sensory cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] This last topographic map of the body onto the posterior central gyrus has been illustrated as a deformed human representation, the somatosensory homunculus, where the size of different body parts reflects the relative density of their innervation.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Areas with much sensory innervation, such as the fingertips and the lips, require more cortical area to process finer sensation.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The motor areas are located in both hemispheres of the cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The motor areas are very closely related to the control of voluntary movements, especially fine fragmented movements performed by the hand.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The right half of the motor area controls the left side of the body, and vice versa.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Just underneath the cerebral cortex are interconnected subcortical masses of grey matter called basal ganglia (or nuclei).
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The basal ganglia receive input from the substantia nigra of the midbrain and motor areas of the cerebral cortex, and send signals back to both of these locations.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The main components of the basal ganglia are the caudate nucleus, the putamen, the globus pallidus, the substantia nigra, the nucleus accumbens, and the subthalamic nucleus.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The putamen and globus pallidus are also collectively known as the lentiform nucleus, because together they form a lens-shaped body.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The putamen and caudate nucleus are also collectively called the corpus striatum after their striped appearance.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The association areas are the parts of the cerebral cortex that do not belong to the primary regions.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] They function to produce a meaningful perceptual experience of the world, enable us to interact effectively, and support abstract thinking and language.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The parietal, temporal, and occipital lobes – all located in the posterior part of the cortex – integrate sensory information and information stored in memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The frontal lobe or prefrontal association complex is involved in planning actions and movement, as well as abstract thought.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Globally, the association areas are organized as distributed networks.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Each network connects areas distributed across widely spaced regions of the cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Distinct networks are positioned adjacent to one another yielding a complex series of interwoven networks.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The specific organization of the association networks is debated with evidence for interactions, hierarchical relationships, and competition between networks.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] In humans, association networks are particularly important to language function.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] In the past it was theorized that language abilities are localized in Broca's area in areas of the left inferior frontal gyrus, BA44 and BA45, for language expression and in Wernicke's area BA22, for language reception.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] However, the processes of language expression and reception have been shown to occur in areas other than just those structures around the lateral sulcus, including the frontal lobe, basal ganglia, cerebellum, and pons.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Neurodegenerative diseases such as Alzheimer's disease, show as a marker, an atrophy of the grey matter of the cerebral cortex.Fractal dimension of the cerebral cortex of patients with Alzheimer's disease differs from the fractal dimension of the cerebral cortex of healthy individuals.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Other diseases of the central nervous system include neurological disorders such as epilepsy, movement disorders, and different types of aphasia (difficulties in speech expression or comprehension).
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Brain damage from disease or trauma, can involve damage to a specific lobe such as in frontal lobe disorder, and associated functions will be affected.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The blood–brain barrier that serves to protect the brain from infection can become compromised allowing entry to pathogens.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The developing fetus is susceptible to a range of environmental factors that can cause birth defects and problems in later development.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Maternal alcohol consumption for example can cause fetal alcohol spectrum disorder.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Other factors that can cause neurodevelopment disorders are toxicants such as drugs, and exposure to radiation as from X-rays.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Infections can also affect the development of the cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] A viral infection is one of the causes of lissencephaly, which results in a smooth cortex without gyrification.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] A type of electrocorticography called cortical stimulation mapping is an invasive procedure that involves placing electrodes directly onto the exposed brain in order to localise the functions of specific areas of the cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] It is used in clinical and therapeutic applications including pre-surgical mapping.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] There are a number of genetic mutations that can cause a wide range of genetic disorders of the cerebral cortex, including microcephaly, schizencephaly and types of lissencephaly.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Chromosome abnormalities can also result causing a number of neurodevelopmental disorders such as fragile X syndrome and Rett syndrome.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] MCPH1 codes for microcephalin, and disorders in this and in ASPM are associated with microcephaly.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Mutations in the gene NBS1 that codes for nibrin can cause Nijmegen breakage syndrome, characterised by microcephaly.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Mutations in EMX2, and COL4A1 are associated with schizencephaly, a condition marked by the absence of large parts of the cerebral hemispheres.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] In 1909, Korbinian Brodmann distinguished 52 different regions of the cerebral cortex based on their cytoarchitecture.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Rafael Lorente de Nó, a student of Santiago Ramon y Cajal, identified more than 40 different types of cortical neurons based on the distribution of their dendrites and axons.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The cerebral cortex is derived from the pallium, a layered structure found in the forebrain of all vertebrates.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The basic form of the pallium is a cylindrical layer enclosing fluid-filled ventricles.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Around the circumference of the cylinder are four zones, the dorsal pallium, medial pallium, ventral pallium, and lateral pallium, which are thought to be homologous to the neocortex, hippocampus, amygdala, and olfactory cortex, respectively.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] In avian brains, evidence suggests the avian pallium's neuroarchitecture to be reminiscent of the mammalian cerebral cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] The avian pallium has also been suggested to be an equivalent neural basis for consciousness.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] Until recently no counterpart to the cerebral cortex had been recognized in invertebrates.
[src:neuroanatomy/cerebral-cortex] However, a study published in the journal *Cell* in 2010, based on gene expression profiles, reported strong affinities between the cerebral cortex and the mushroom bodies of the ragworm *Platynereis dumerilii*.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The **hippocampus** (pl.: **hippocampi**), also **hippocampus proper**, is a major component of the brain of humans and many other vertebrates.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] In the human brain the hippocampus, the dentate gyrus, and the subiculum are components of the hippocampal formation located in the limbic system.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The hippocampus plays important roles in the consolidation of information from short-term memory to long-term memory, and in spatial memory that enables navigation.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] In humans and other primates the hippocampus is located in the archicortex, one of the three regions of allocortex, in each hemisphere with direct neural projections to, and reciprocal indirect projections from the neocortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The hippocampus, as the medial pallium, is a structure found in all vertebrates.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] In Alzheimer's disease (and other forms of dementia), the hippocampus is one of the first regions of the brain to be damaged; short-term memory loss and disorientation are included among the early symptoms.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Damage to the hippocampus can also result from oxygen starvation (hypoxia), encephalitis, or medial temporal lobe epilepsy.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] People with extensive, bilateral hippocampal damage may experience anterograde amnesia: the inability to form and retain new memories.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Since different neuronal cell types are neatly organized into layers in the hippocampus, it has frequently been used as a model system for studying neurophysiology.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The form of neural plasticity known as long-term potentiation (LTP) was initially discovered to occur in the hippocampus and has often been studied in this structure.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] LTP is widely believed to be one of the main neural mechanisms by which memories are stored in the brain.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Using rodents as model organisms, the hippocampus has been studied extensively as part of a brain system responsible for spatial memory and navigation.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Many neurons in the rat and mouse hippocampi respond as place cells: that is, they fire bursts of action potentials when the animal passes through a specific part of its environment.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Hippocampal place cells interact extensively with head direction cells, whose activity acts as an inertial compass, and conjecturally with grid cells in the neighboring entorhinal cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The German anatomist Johann Georg Duvernoy (1729), the first to illustrate the structure, also wavered between "seahorse" and "silkworm".
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] "Ram's horn" was proposed by the Danish anatomist Jacob Winsløw in 1732; and a decade later his fellow Parisian, the surgeon de Garengeot, used *cornu Ammonis* – horn of Amun, after the ancient Egyptian god who was often represented as having a ram's head.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The head region of the hippocampus is enlarged, and presents two or three rounded elevations or foot-like digitations, and hence it was named the **pes hippocampi** (*pes* meaning *foot*).
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Later this part was described as *pes hippocampi major*, with an adjacent bulge in the occipital horn of the lateral ventricle, described as *pes hippocampi minor* later renamed as the calcar avis.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] In 1786 Félix Vicq-d'Azyr published an authoritative description naming just the *hippocampus* but the term remained largely unused with no description of any function proposed until in the middle of the 20th century it was associated with memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Mayer mistakenly used the term hippopotamus in 1779, and was followed by some other authors until Karl Friedrich Burdach resolved this error in 1829.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] In 1861 the hippocampus minor became the center of a dispute over human evolution between Thomas Henry Huxley and Richard Owen, satirized as the Great Hippocampus Question.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The term hippocampus minor fell from use in anatomy textbooks and was officially removed in the Nomina Anatomica of 1895.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The modern term for the structure is just the hippocampus, with the term *cornu Ammonis* (that is, 'Ammon's horn') surviving in the names of the hippocampal subfields CA1–CA4.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The hippocampus is one of the structures of the limbic lobe, first described by Broca in 1878, as the cortical areas that line the deep edge of the cerebral cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The limbic lobe is the main component of the limbic system.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The cingulate gyrus, and the parahippocampal gyrus are the two main parts of the described lobe, which had been largely associated with olfaction.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Many studies later culminating in work by Papez, and MacLean, the involvement of other interacting brain regions associated with emotion was recognized.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The hippocampus is anatomically connected to parts of the brain that are involved with emotional behavior, including the septal area, the hypothalamic mammillary bodies, and the anterior nuclear complex in the thalamus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] MacLean proposed that the associated structures of the limbic lobe be included in what he termed as the *limbic system*.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The hippocampus is a five centimeter long ridge of gray matter tissue within the parahippocampal gyrus that can only be seen when the gyrus is opened.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The hippocampus is an inward fold of three-layered archicortex (one of three regions of the allocortex) into the medial temporal lobe of the brain, where it elevates into the floor of each lateral ventricle inferior horn.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The hippocampus stretches along its anterior-posterior axis, from the amygdala to the splenium of the corpus callosum, with the head, body, and tail as subregions of this axis.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The dentate gyrus, CA subfields, fimbria, and subiculum are divisions across the short axis, the proximal-distal axis.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The hippocampal formation refers to the hippocampus, and its related adjoining parts to include the dentate gyrus, the subiculum, the presubiculum, parasubiculum, and the entorhinal cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Sometimes the subiculum, presubiculum, and parasubiculum are grouped together as the *subicular complex*, but the regions are neuroanatomically distinct.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Some sources may only include the hippocampus, dentate gyrus, and subiculum, being regions of the hippocampal three-layered archicortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] But the six regions are linked together serially by almost unidirectional neural pathways.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Other sources include the indusium griseum, gyrus fasciolaris, the medial and longitudinal striae, and uncus, and exclude subicular regions.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The neural layout and pathways within the hippocampal formation are very similar in all mammals.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The hippocampus has a generally similar appearance across the range of mammals, from egg-laying mammals such as the echidna, to humans and other primates.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The hippocampal-size-to-body-size ratio broadly increases, being about twice as large for primates as for the echidna.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] It does not, however, increase at anywhere close to the rate of the neocortex-to-body-size ratio.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Therefore, the hippocampus takes up a much larger fraction of the cortical mantle in rodents than in primates.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] In adult humans the volume of the hippocampus on each side of the brain is about 3.0 to 3.5 cm3 as compared to 320 to 420 cm3 for the volume of the neocortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] There is also a general relationship between the size of the hippocampus and spatial memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] When comparisons are made between similar species, those that have a greater capacity for spatial memory tend to have larger hippocampal volumes.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The hippocampus and dentate gyrus that is folded into the hippocampal archicortex have the shape of a curved, rolled-up tube.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The curve of the hippocampus (known as *cornu Ammonis*) uses the initial letters *CA* to name the hippocampal subfields CA1-CA4.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] CA4 is in fact the polymorphic layer or hilus of the dentate gyrus, but CA4 is still sometimes in use to describe the part of CA3 that inserts between the dentate gyrus regions or *blades*.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] It can be distinguished as an area where the cortex narrows into a single layer of densely packed pyramidal neurons, which curl into a tight U shape.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] One edge of the "U" is CA4, the hilus of the dentate gyrus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] This is embedded into the backward-facing, flexed dentate gyrus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] In humans the hippocampus is described as having an anterior and posterior part; in other primates they are termed rostral and caudal, and in rodents they are termed ventral and dorsal.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Both parts are of similar composition but belong to different neural circuits.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The dentate gyrus combined with other hippocampal regions form a banana-like structure, with the two hippocampi joined at the stems by the commissure of fornix (also called the hippocampal commissure).
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] In humans and other primates, the part of the hippocampus at the bottom, near the base of the temporal lobe, is much broader than the part at the top.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] This means that in cross-section the hippocampus can show a number of different shapes, depending on the angle and location of the cut.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] In a cross-section of the hippocampus, including the dentate gyrus, several layers will be shown.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The dentate gyrus has three layers of cells – the outer *molecular layer*, the middle *granular layer*, and the inner *polymorphic layer* also known as the *hilus*.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The CA3 subfield has the following cell layers known as strata: lacunosum-moleculare, radiatum, lucidum, pyramidal, and oriens.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] CA2 and CA1 also have these layers except the lucidum stratum.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The input to the hippocampus (from varying cortical and subcortical structures) comes from the entorhinal cortex via the perforant path.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The entorhinal cortex (EC) is strongly and reciprocally connected with many cortical and subcortical structures as well as with the brainstem.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The EC is located in the parahippocampal gyrus, a cortical region adjacent to the hippocampus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The parahippocampal gyrus is adjacent to the perirhinal cortex, which plays an important role in the visual recognition of complex objects.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] There is also substantial evidence that it makes a contribution to memory, which can be distinguished from the contribution of the hippocampus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] It is apparent that complete amnesia occurs only when both the hippocampus and the parahippocampus are damaged.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The major input to the hippocampus is through the entorhinal cortex (EC), whereas its major output is via CA1 to the subiculum.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Information reaches CA1 via two main pathways, direct and indirect.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Axons from the EC that originate in layer III are the origin of the direct perforant pathway and form synapses on the very distal apical dendrites of CA1 neurons.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Conversely, axons originating from layer II are the origin of the indirect pathway, and information reaches CA1 via the trisynaptic circuit.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] In the initial part of this pathway, the axons project through the perforant pathway to the granule cells of the dentate gyrus (first synapse).
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] From then, the information follows via the mossy cell fibers to CA3 (second synapse).
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] From there, CA3 axons called Schaffer collaterals leave the deep part of the cell body and loop up to the apical dendrites and then extend to CA1 (third synapse).
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Axons from CA1 then project back to the entorhinal cortex, completing the circuit.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Basket cells in CA3 receive excitatory input from the pyramidal cells and then give an inhibitory feedback to the pyramidal cells.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] This *recurrent inhibition* is a simple feedback circuit that can dampen excitatory responses in the hippocampus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The pyramidal cells give a *recurrent excitation* which is an important mechanism found in some memory processing microcircuits.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Several other connections play important roles in hippocampal function.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Beyond the output to the EC, additional output pathways go to other cortical areas including the prefrontal cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] A major output goes via the fornix to the lateral septal area and to the mammillary body of the hypothalamus (which the fornix interconnects with the hippocampus).
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The hippocampus receives modulatory input from the serotonin, norepinephrine, and dopamine systems, and from the nucleus reuniens of the thalamus to field CA1.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] A very important projection comes from the medial septal nucleus, which sends cholinergic, and gamma amino butyric acid (GABA) stimulating fibers (GABAergic fibers) to all parts of the hippocampus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The inputs from the medial septal nucleus play a key role in controlling the physiological state of the hippocampus; destruction of this nucleus abolishes the hippocampal theta rhythm and impairs spatial memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The hippocampal subfields (CA1-CA4), and subregions, head, body, and tail, are functionally and anatomically differentiated, and connect differently to other brain regions.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Their cells are morphologically different.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] They also have different levels of vulnerability to disease.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] In humans the head of the hippocampus is also termed the anterior hippocampus, the body is the intermediate hippocampus, and the tail the posterior hippocampus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The terms used for corresponding subregions in other primates are anterior (or rostral), intermediate and posterior (or caudal) and in rodents ventral or temporal, intermediate and dorsal (or septal).
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The subregions along the longitudinal axis have been linked to different functions, project with different neural pathways, and have varying numbers of place cells with differentially sized place fields.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] For example, the posterior hippocampus has particularly been linked to spatial memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] In the rat, the dorsal hippocampus has more place cells than both the ventral and intermediate hippocampal regions, and place cells in the dorsal hippocampal provide a more fine-grained representation of the spatial environment than in the intermediate and ventral hippocampus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The intermediate hippocampus has overlapping characteristics with both the ventral and dorsal hippocampus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Studies in 2002, showed that alterations to the ventral hippocampus reduced the amount of information sent to the amygdala by the dorsal and ventral hippocampus, consequently altering fear conditioning in rats.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] In 2007, studies using anterograde tracing methods, located the moderate projections to two primary olfactory cortical areas and prelimbic areas of the medial prefrontal cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] This region has the smallest number of place cells.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The ventral hippocampus has been particularly linked to fear conditioning and affective processes.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Three main theories of hippocampal function have been in dominance: response inhibition, episodic memory, and spatial cognition.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The response inhibition theory (caricatured by John O'Keefe and Lynn Nadel as "slam on the brakes!") was very popular up to the 1960s.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] British psychologist Jeffrey Gray developed this line of thought into a complete theory of the role of the hippocampus in anxiety, called the behavioral inhibition system.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The second major line of thought relates the hippocampus to memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Although it had historical precursors, this idea derived its main impetus from a famous report by American neurosurgeon William Beecher Scoville and British-Canadian neuropsychologist Brenda Milner.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] This case attracted such widespread professional interest that Molaison became the most intensively studied subject in medical history.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The third important theory of hippocampal function relates the hippocampus to space, and spatial memory, with the idea of a cognitive map first proposed by American psychologist E.C.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] This theory was followed further by O'Keefe, and in 1971, he and his student Dostrovsky discovered neurons in the rat hippocampus that seemed to show activity related to the rat's location within its environment.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The neurons were described as place cells.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] A book was later produced in 1978, *The Hippocampus as a Cognitive Map* written by O'Keefe and Nadel.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] It has been generally agreed that the hippocampus plays a key role in spatial coding but the details are widely debated.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Research has focused on trying to bridge the disconnect between the two main views of hippocampal function as being split between memory and spatial cognition.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] In some studies, these areas have been expanded to the point of near convergence.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] This relates to the purposive behaviorism born of Tolman's original goal of identifying the complex cognitive mechanisms and purposes that guided behavior.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] It has also been proposed that the spiking activity of hippocampal neurons is associated spatially, and it was suggested that the mechanisms of memory and planning both evolved from mechanisms of navigation and that their neuronal algorithms were basically the same.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Many studies have made use of neuroimaging techniques such as functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI), and a functional role in approach-avoidance conflict has been noted.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The anterior hippocampus is seen to be involved in decision-making under approach-avoidance conflict processing.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] It is suggested that the memory, spatial cognition, and conflict processing functions may be seen as working together and not mutually exclusive.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The hallmark function of the hippocampus is the formation of explicit memory, also known as declarative memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Episodic memory, and semantic memory are the two components of explicit memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The hippocampus also encodes emotional context from the amygdala.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] This is partly why returning to a location where an emotional event occurred may evoke that emotion.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] There is a deep emotional connection between episodic memories and places.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Due to bilateral symmetry the brain has a hippocampus in each cerebral hemisphere.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] If damage to the hippocampus occurs in only one hemisphere, leaving the structure intact in the other hemisphere, the brain can retain near-normal memory functioning.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Severe damage to the hippocampi in both hemispheres results in profound difficulties in forming new memories (anterograde amnesia) and often also affects memories formed before the damage occurred (retrograde amnesia).
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Although the retrograde effect normally extends many years back before the brain damage, in some cases older memories remain.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] This retention of older memories leads to the idea that consolidation over time involves the transfer of memories out of the hippocampus to other parts of the brain.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Experiments using intrahippocampal transplantation of hippocampal cells in primates with neurotoxic lesions of the hippocampus have shown that the hippocampus is required for the formation and recall, but not the storage, of memories.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] It has been shown that a decrease in the volume of various parts of the hippocampus leads to specific memory impairments.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] In particular, efficiency of verbal memory retention is related to the anterior parts of the right and left hippocampus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The right head of the hippocampus is more involved in executive functions and regulation during verbal memory recall.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The tail of the left hippocampus tends to be closely related to verbal memory capacity.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Damage to the hippocampus does not affect some types of memory, such as the ability to learn new skills (playing a musical instrument or solving certain types of puzzles, for example).
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] This fact suggests that such abilities depend on different types of memory such as procedural memory in implicit memory function, implicating different brain regions.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Furthermore, amnesic patients frequently show implicit memory for experiences even in the absence of conscious knowledge.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] For example, patients asked to guess which of two faces they have seen most recently may give the correct answer most of the time in spite of stating that they have never seen either of the faces before.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Some researchers distinguish between conscious *recollection*, which depends on the hippocampus, and *familiarity*, which depends on portions of the medial temporal lobe.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] A study claims to have confirmed that the hippocampus is not associated with implicit memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] But other sources say the question is still up for debate (as of 2024).
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] When rats are exposed to an intense learning event, they may retain a life-long memory of the event even after a single training session.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The memory of such an event appears to be first stored in the hippocampus, but this storage is transient.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Much of the long-term storage of the memory seems to take place in the anterior cingulate cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] When such an intense learning event was experimentally applied, more than 5,000 differently methylated DNA regions appeared in the hippocampus neuronal genome of the rats at one hour and at 24 hours after training.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] These alterations in methylation pattern occurred at many genes that were down-regulated, often due to the formation of new 5-methylcytosine sites in CpG rich regions of the genome.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Furthermore, many other genes were upregulated, likely often due to the removal of methyl groups from previously existing 5-methylcytosines (5mCs) in DNA.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Demethylation of 5mC can be carried out by several proteins acting in concert, including TET enzymes as well as enzymes of the DNA base excision repair pathway.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The **between-systems memory interference model** describes the inhibition of non-hippocampal systems of memory during concurrent hippocampal activity.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Specifically it was found that when the hippocampus was inactive, non-hippocampal systems located elsewhere in the brain were found to consolidate memory in its place.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] However, when the hippocampus was reactivated, memory traces consolidated by non-hippocampal systems were not recalled, suggesting that the hippocampus interferes with long-term memory consolidation in other memory-related systems.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] One of the major implications that this model illustrates is the dominant effects of the hippocampus on non-hippocampal networks when information is incongruent.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] With this information in mind, future directions could lead towards the study of these non-hippocampal memory systems through hippocampal inactivation, further expanding the labile constructs of memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Additionally, many theories of memory are holistically based around the hippocampus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] This model could add beneficial information to hippocampal research and memory theories such as the multiple trace theory.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Lastly, the between-system memory interference model allows researchers to evaluate their results on a multiple-systems model, suggesting that some effects may not be simply mediated by one portion of the brain.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] There are several types of navigational cells in the brain that are either in the hippocampus itself or are strongly connected to it.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] They include the place cells, speed cells present in the medial entorhinal cortex, head direction cells, grid cells, and boundary cells.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Together these cells form a network that serves as spatial memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The first of these types of cell discovered in the 1970s were the place cells, which led to the idea of the hippocampus acting to give a neural representation of the environment in a cognitive map.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] When the hippocampus is dysfunctional, orientation is affected; people may have difficulty in remembering how they arrived at a location and how to proceed further.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Getting lost is a common symptom of amnesia.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Studies with animals have shown that an intact hippocampus is required for initial learning and long-term retention of some spatial memory tasks, in particular ones that require finding the way to a hidden goal.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Studies on freely moving rats and mice have shown many hippocampal neurons to act as place cells that cluster in place fields, and these fire bursts of action potentials when the animal passes through a particular location.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Speed cells are thought to provide input to the hippocampal grid cells.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] This place-related neural activity in the hippocampus has also been reported in monkeys that were moved around a room whilst in a restraint chair.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] However, the place cells may have fired in relation to where the monkey was looking rather than to its actual location in the room.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Over many years, many studies have been carried out on place-responses in rodents, which have given a large amount of information.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Place cell responses are shown by pyramidal cells in the hippocampus and by granule cells in the dentate gyrus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Other cells in smaller proportion are inhibitory interneurons, and these often show place-related variations in their firing rate that are much weaker.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] There is little, if any, spatial topography in the representation; in general, cells lying next to each other in the hippocampus have uncorrelated spatial firing patterns.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Place cells are typically almost silent when a rat is moving around outside the place field but reach sustained rates as high as 40 Hz when the rat is near the center.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Neural activity sampled from 30 to 40 randomly chosen place cells carries enough information to allow a rat's location to be reconstructed with high confidence.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The size of place fields varies in a gradient along the length of the hippocampus, with cells at the dorsal end showing the smallest fields, cells near the center showing larger fields, and cells at the ventral tip showing fields that cover the entire environment.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] In some cases, the firing rate of hippocampal cells depends not only on place but also the direction a rat is moving, the destination toward which it is traveling, or other task-related variables.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The firing of place cells is timed in relation to local theta waves, a spatiotemporal process termed phase precession.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Cells with location-specific firing patterns have been reported during a study of people with drug-resistant epilepsy.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] They were undergoing an invasive procedure to localize the source of their seizures, with a view to surgical resection.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] They had diagnostic electrodes implanted in their hippocampi and then used a computer to move around in a virtual reality town.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Similar brain imaging studies in navigation have shown the hippocampus to be active.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] A study was carried out on taxi drivers.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] London's black cab drivers need to learn the locations of a large number of places and the fastest routes between them in order to pass a strict test known as The Knowledge in order to gain a license to operate.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] A study showed that the posterior part of the hippocampus is larger in these drivers than in the general public, and that a positive correlation exists between the length of time served as a driver and the increase in the volume of this part.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] It was also found the total volume of the hippocampus was unchanged, as the increase seen in the posterior part was made at the expense of the anterior part, which showed a relative decrease in size.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] There have been no reported adverse effects from this disparity in hippocampal proportions.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Another study showed opposite findings in blind individuals.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The anterior part of the right hippocampus was larger and the posterior part was smaller, compared with sighted individuals.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Overall findings showed that the anterior hippocampus is sensitive to conflict, and that it may be part of a larger cortical and subcortical network seen to be important in decision-making in uncertain conditions.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] A review makes reference to a number of studies that show the involvement of the hippocampus in conflict tasks.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The authors suggest that one challenge is to understand how conflict processing relates to the functions of spatial navigation and memory and how all of these functions need not be mutually exclusive.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The hippocampus has received renewed attention for its role in social memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Epileptic human subjects with depth electrodes in the left posterior, left anterior or right anterior hippocampus demonstrate distinct, individual cell responses when presented with faces of presumably recognizable famous people.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Associations among facial and vocal identity were similarly mapped to the hippocampus of rhesus monkeys.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Single neurons in the CA1 and CA3 responded strongly to social stimulus recognition by MRI.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The CA2 was not distinguished, and may likely comprise a proportion of the claimed CA1 cells in the study.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The dorsal CA2 and ventral CA1 subregions of the hippocampus have been implicated in social memory processing.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Genetic inactivation of CA2 pyramidal neurons leads to pronounced loss of social memory, while maintaining intact sociability in mice.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Similarly, ventral CA1 pyramidal neurons have also been demonstrated as critical for social memory under optogenetic control in mice.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] In the early 20th century, the widely held view was that olfaction was a major hippocampal function.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] This view was argued against, pointing out that the hippocampus was present in some animals such as dolphins and whales, that did not have a sense of smell; and further that lesions in the temporal lobe in dogs had been shown to have no effect on their sense of smell.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] These arguments were concluded in 1947 and held for a few more decades.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] In 1984, and 1987, studies in the rat showed that the entorhinal cortex receives substantial input from the olfactory bulb, with part of the EC being directly innervated by the lateral olfactory tract.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Secondary inputs to the EC were also shown to include some from the periamygdaloid and piriform cortices, and CA1 in the ventral hippocampus was shown to sends axons to the main olfactory bulb.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] It is evident that the hippocampus does have an involvement in memory for odors.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The hippocampus shows two major modes of activity, each associated with a distinct pattern of neural population activity and waves of electrical activity as measured by an electroencephalogram (EEG).
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] These modes are named after the EEG patterns associated with them: theta and large irregular activity (LIA).
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The main characteristics described below are for the rat, which is the animal most extensively studied.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The theta mode appears during states of active, alert behavior (especially locomotion), and also during REM sleep (dreaming).
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] An active cell typically stays active for half a second to a few seconds.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] As the rat behaves, the active cells fall silent and new cells become active, but the overall percentage of active cells remains more or less constant.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] In many situations, cell activity is determined largely by the spatial location of the animal, but other behavioral variables also clearly influence it.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The LIA mode appears during slow-wave sleep (non-dreaming), and also during states of waking immobility such as resting or eating.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] In the LIA mode, the EEG is dominated by sharp waves that are randomly timed large deflections of the EEG signal lasting for 25–50 milliseconds.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Sharp waves are frequently generated in sets, with sets containing up to 5 or more individual sharp waves and lasting up to 500 ms.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The spiking activity of neurons within the hippocampus is highly correlated with sharp wave activity.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Most neurons decrease their firing rate between sharp waves; however, during a sharp wave, there is a dramatic increase in firing rate in up to 10% of the hippocampal population.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] These two hippocampal activity modes can be seen in primates as well as rats, with the exception that it has been difficult to see robust theta rhythmicity in the primate hippocampus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] There are, however, qualitatively similar sharp waves and similar state-dependent changes in neural population activity.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The underlying currents producing the theta wave are generated mainly by densely packed neural layers of the entorhinal cortex, CA3, and the dendrites of pyramidal cells.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The theta wave is one of the largest signals seen on EEG, and is known as the hippocampal theta rhythm.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] In some situations the EEG is dominated by regular waves at 3 to 10 Hz, often continuing for many seconds.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] These reflect subthreshold membrane potentials and strongly modulate the spiking of hippocampal neurons and synchronize across the hippocampus in a travelling wave pattern.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The trisynaptic circuit is a relay of neurotransmission in the hippocampus that interacts with many brain regions.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] From rodent studies it has been proposed that the trisynaptic circuit generates the hippocampal theta rhythm.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Theta rhythmicity previously clearly shown in rabbits and rodents has also been shown in humans.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] In rats (the animals that have been the most extensively studied), theta is seen mainly in two conditions: first, when an animal is walking or in some other way actively interacting with its surroundings; second, during REM sleep.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The function of theta has not yet been convincingly explained although numerous theories have been proposed.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The most popular hypothesis has been to relate it to learning and memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] An example would be the phase with which theta rhythms, at the time of stimulation of a neuron, shape the effect of that stimulation upon its synapses.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] What is meant here is that theta rhythms may affect those aspects of learning and memory that are dependent upon synaptic plasticity.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] It is well established that lesions of the medial septum – the central node of the theta system – cause severe disruptions of memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] However, the medial septum is more than just the controller of theta; it is also the main source of cholinergic projections to the hippocampus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] It has not been established that septal lesions exert their effects specifically by eliminating the theta rhythm.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] During sleep or during resting, when an animal is not engaged with its surroundings, the hippocampal EEG shows a pattern of irregular slow waves, somewhat larger in amplitude than theta waves.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] This pattern is occasionally interrupted by large surges called *sharp waves*.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] These events are associated with bursts of spike activity lasting 50 to 100 milliseconds in pyramidal cells of CA3 and CA1.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] They are also associated with short-lived high-frequency EEG oscillations called "ripples", with frequencies in the range 150 to 200 Hz in rats, and together they are known as sharp waves and ripples.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Sharp waves are most frequent during sleep when they occur at an average rate of around 1 per second (in rats) but in a very irregular temporal pattern.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Sharp waves are less frequent during inactive waking states and are usually smaller.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Sharp waves have also been observed in humans and monkeys.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] In macaques, sharp waves are robust but do not occur as frequently as in rats.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Sharp waves appear to be associated with memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Numerous later studies, have reported that when hippocampal place cells have overlapping spatial firing fields (and therefore often fire in near-simultaneity), they tend to show correlated activity during sleep following the behavioral session.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] This enhancement of correlation, commonly known as *reactivation*, has been found to occur mainly during sharp waves.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] It has been proposed that sharp waves are, in fact, reactivations of neural activity patterns that were memorized during behavior, driven by strengthening of synaptic connections within the hippocampus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] This idea forms a key component of the "two-stage memory" theory, advocated by Buzsáki and others, which proposes that memories are stored within the hippocampus during behavior and then later transferred to the neocortex during sleep.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Sharp waves in Hebbian theory are seen as persistently repeated stimulations by presynaptic cells, of postsynaptic cells that are suggested to drive synaptic changes in the cortical targets of hippocampal output pathways.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Suppression of sharp waves and ripples in sleep or during immobility can interfere with memories expressed at the level of the behavior, nonetheless, the newly formed CA1 place cell code can re-emerge even after a sleep with abolished sharp waves and ripples, in spatially non-demanding tasks.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Since at least the time of Ramon y Cajal (1852–1934), psychologists have speculated that the brain stores memory by altering the strength of connections between neurons that are simultaneously active.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] This idea was formalized by Donald Hebb in 1949, but for many years remained unexplained.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] In 1973, Tim Bliss and Terje Lømo described a phenomenon in the rabbit hippocampus that appeared to meet Hebb's specifications: a change in synaptic responsiveness induced by brief strong activation and lasting for hours or days or longer.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] This phenomenon was soon referred to as long-term potentiation (LTP).
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] As a candidate mechanism for long-term memory, LTP has since been studied intensively, and a great deal has been learned about it.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] However, the complexity and variety of the intracellular signaling cascades that can trigger LTP is acknowledged as preventing a more complete understanding.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The hippocampus is a particularly favorable site for studying LTP because of its densely packed and sharply defined layers of neurons, but similar types of activity-dependent synaptic change have also been observed in many other brain areas.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The best-studied form of LTP has been seen in CA1 of the hippocampus and occurs at synapses that terminate on dendritic spines and use the neurotransmitter glutamate.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] The synaptic changes depend on the *N*-methyl-D-aspartate (NMDA) receptor, a cell surface receptor that allows calcium to enter the postsynaptic spine when glutamate and glycine are bound and postsynaptic depolarization occur at the same time.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Drugs that interfere with NMDA receptors block LTP and have major effects on some types of memory, especially spatial memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] Genetically modified mice that are modified to disable the LTP mechanism also generally show severe memory deficits.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] A brain implant for use as a hippocampal prosthesis has been the subject of research since the early 2000s.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] It was reported in 2018 that a nonlinear multi-input multi-output model (MIMO) had been developed that in some studies, had been shown to restore and improve memory function.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] This has been followed by a modified version known as the memory decoding model (MDM).
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] This model has been shown to have the potential use in significant modification of memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p01] A study concluded that further research could be pointed towards an evaluation of both models, in particular focusing on the hippocampal theta wave input.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Normal aging is associated with a gradual decline in some types of memory, including episodic memory and working memory (or short-term memory).
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Because the hippocampus plays a central role in memory, there has been considerable interest in the possibility that age-related declines could be caused by hippocampal deterioration.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Studies show that hippocampal volume loss is a noted feature from middle age, more so in women than in men.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Where there is age-related shrinkage, memory performance will be impaired.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] There are also reports that memory tasks tend to produce less hippocampal activation in the elderly than in the young.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Furthermore, a randomized control trial published in 2011 found that aerobic exercise could increase the size of the hippocampus in adults aged 55 to 80 and also improve spatial memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] In Alzheimer's disease, (and other forms of dementia) the hippocampus is one of the first regions of the brain to be damaged; short-term memory loss and disorientation are included among the early symptoms.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Amyloid beta deposits begin in the frontal lobes before the signs of neurofibrillary tangles are seen in the hippocampus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Extensive, bilateral hippocampal damage may cause anterograde amnesia: the inability to form and retain new memories.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Dementia is very often caused by cerebral ischemia that is believed to trigger changes in the hippocampus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Changes in CA1, the hippocampal area that underlies episodic memory, cause episodic memory impairment, the earliest symptom of post-ischemic dementia.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] The hippocampus contains high levels of glucocorticoid receptors, which make it more vulnerable to long-term stress than most other brain areas.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] There is evidence that humans having experienced severe, long-lasting traumatic stress show atrophy of the hippocampus more than of other parts of the brain.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] These effects show up in post-traumatic stress disorder, and they may contribute to the hippocampal atrophy reported in schizophrenia and severe depression.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Anterior hippocampal volume in children is positively correlated with parental family income and this correlation is thought to be mediated by income-related stress.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] A study has revealed atrophy as a result of depression, but this can be stopped with anti-depressants even if they are not effective in relieving other symptoms.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Chronic stress resulting in elevated levels of glucocorticoids, notably of cortisol, is seen to be a cause of neuronal atrophy in the hippocampus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] This atrophy results in a smaller hippocampal volume which is also seen in Cushing's syndrome.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] The higher levels of cortisol in Cushing's syndrome is usually the result of medications taken for other conditions.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Neuronal loss also occurs as a result of impaired neurogenesis.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Another factor that contributes to a smaller hippocampal volume is that of dendritic retraction where dendrites are shortened in length and reduced in number, in response to increased glucocorticoids.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] This dendritic retraction is reversible.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] After treatment with medication to reduce cortisol in Cushing's syndrome, the hippocampal volume is seen to be restored by as much as 10%.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] This change is seen to be due to the reforming of the dendrites.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] This dendritic restoration can also happen when stress is removed.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] There is, however, evidence derived mainly from studies using rats that stress occurring shortly after birth can affect hippocampal function in ways that persist throughout life.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Sex-specific responses to stress have also been demonstrated in the rat to have an effect on the hippocampus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Chronic stress in the male rat showed dendritic retraction and cell loss in the CA3 region but this was not shown in the female.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] This was thought to be due to neuroprotective ovarian hormones.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] In rats, DNA damage increases in the hippocampus under conditions of stress.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Some studies shows correlation of reduced hippocampus volume and post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD).
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] A study of Vietnam War combat veterans with PTSD showed a 20% reduction in the volume of their hippocampus compared with veterans with no such symptoms.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] This finding was not replicated in those with chronic PTSD, traumatized at an air show plane crash in 1988 (Ramstein, Germany).
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] It is also the case that non-combat twin brothers of Vietnam veterans with PTSD also had smaller hippocampi than other controls, raising questions about the nature of the correlation.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] A 2016 study strengthened the theory that a smaller hippocampus increases the risk for post-traumatic stress disorder, and a larger hippocampus increases the likelihood of efficacious treatment.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Transient global amnesia is a syndrome of unknown cause that results in a sudden and temporary anterograde amnesia and variable past memory loss.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] An attack usually lasts for up to 24 hours during which time the memory loss is experienced.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] The only diagnostic evidence of TGA is given by DWI-MRI that shows lesions as small dots in the CA1 subfield.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] The lesions are detectable from around 24 to 96 hours after symptoms onset, and can be seen to have been resolved at a six-month follow-up.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] The lesions are between 1 and 5 mm, and can be single or multiple and may be confined to either hemisphere.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Lesions in the dominant hemisphere affect episodic verbal memory and those in the non-dominant hemisphere affect visuospatial memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] CA1 lesions shows selective affect over other CA subfields.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] The selective vulnerability of CA1 neurons suggests a cause of metabolic stress that could result from emotional or behavioral stress.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Other possible causes have been debated including cerebral venous reflex, arterial ischema, epilepsy, and migraine.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] TGA as a *network disease* has also been put forward; DTI studies show a decreased connectivity between brain regions that may impact the hippocampus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] The hippocampus is one of the few brain regions where new neurons are generated.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] This process of neurogenesis is confined to the dentate gyrus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Neurogenesis can be positively affected by exercise or negatively affected by epileptic seizures.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Seizures in temporal lobe epilepsy can affect the normal development of new neurons and can cause tissue damage.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Hippocampal sclerosis specific to the mesial temporal lobe, is the most common type of such tissue damage.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] It is not yet clear, however, whether the epilepsy is usually caused by hippocampal abnormalities or whether the hippocampus is damaged by cumulative effects of seizures.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] However, in experimental settings where repetitive seizures are artificially induced in animals, hippocampal damage is a frequent result.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] This may be a consequence of the concentration of excitable glutamate receptors in the hippocampus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Hyperexcitability can lead to cytotoxicity and cell death.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] It may also have something to do with the hippocampus being a site of continuous neurogenesis, and to abnormalities in this process.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] A reduction in hippocampal volume is well reported in those with schizophrenia.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] The left hippocampus seems to be affected more than the right.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] The volume reduction is small but consistent, it can be first seen in the prodromal stage, and can show modest progression as the disease advances.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] The reduced volume has been shown to be independent of treatment with antipsychotics.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Some studies suggest that hippocampal alterations play a role in causing the psychotic symptoms of schizophrenia.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] It has been suggested that hippocampal dysfunction might produce an alteration of dopamine release in the basal ganglia, thereby indirectly affecting the integration of information in the prefrontal cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] In those with psychosis the greatest reduction is seen to be in CA3 and CA2 subfields, and a correlation has been made between the reduced volume and memory dysfunction.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] A reduced hippocampal volume has been shown to result in a decreased connectivity between the hippocampus and the prefrontal cortex, with the declarative memory characteristic of hippocampal function becoming selectively impaired.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] The impaired connectivity is evident both at rest and during task-activity.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Evidence of dysfunctional GABA (inhibitory) transmission has been shown in studies of the whole hippocampus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Another noted change in the hippocampus is a reduced M4 muscarinic cholinergic receptor, but an unaffected M1 receptor.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Reduced neurogenesis has been shown in the dentate gyrus with a noted reduction in the density of neurons and oligodendrocytes.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Hyperactivity in the hippocampus has consistently been linked to schizophrenia using blood-oxygenation-level–dependent imaging in functional MRI, and in cerebral blood volume studies.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] The CA1 subfield is mostly indicated to be affected, and hyperactivity almost exclusively found in the anterior hippocampus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Hippocampal hyperactivity has been suggested to be a result of dysfunctional GABAergic inhibition.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] It has been suggested that hippocampal hyperactivity at early stages of schizophrenia may contribute, by excitotoxic mechanisms, to hippocampal atrophy and volume reduction at later stages of the disorder.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Hippocampal hyperactivity has been suggested to contribute to symptoms of schizophrenia, including those of psychosis.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Hippocampus atrophy has been characterized in those with microcephaly.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Mouse models with Wdr62 mutations which recapitulate human point mutations show a deficiency in hippocampal development, and neurogenesis.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Non-mammalian vertebrates lack a brain structure that looks like the mammalian hippocampus, but they have one that is considered homologous to it.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] The hippocampus is in essence part of the allocortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Only mammals have a fully developed cortex, but the structure it evolved from, called the pallium, is present in all vertebrates, even the most primitive ones such as the lamprey or hagfish.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] The pallium is usually divided into three zones: medial, lateral and dorsal.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] The medial pallium forms the precursor of the hippocampus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] It does not resemble the hippocampus visually because the layers are not warped into an S shape or enfolded by the dentate gyrus, but the homology is indicated by strong chemical and functional affinities.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] There is evidence that these hippocampal-like structures are involved in spatial cognition in reptiles, and in fish.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] In teleost fish, the forebrain is everted (like an inside-out sock) with structures that lie on the outside, as contrasted with other vertebrate structures that lie in the interior, next to the ventricles.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] One of the consequences of this is that the medial pallium, the hippocampal zone of a typical vertebrate, is thought to correspond to the lateral pallium of a typical fish.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Several types of fish (particularly goldfish) have been shown experimentally to have strong spatial memory abilities, even forming cognitive maps of the areas they inhabit.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Studies in goldfish show that damage to both the lateral pallium, and the medial pallium impairs spatial memory coding.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] It is not clear if the medial pallium plays a similar role in basal vertebrates, such as sharks and rays, or even lampreys and hagfish.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] The dorsolateral pallium of the teleost is considered as homologous to the hippocampus in terrestrial vertebrates.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] In 2023, the goldfish brain was mapped by molecular parcellization showing that its telencephalon subregions were homogeneous to the hippocampal subfields in the mouse.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] In birds, the correspondence is sufficiently well established that most anatomists refer to the medial pallial zone as the "avian hippocampus".
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Numerous species of birds have strong spatial skills, in particular those that cache (store) food.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] There is evidence that food-caching birds have a larger hippocampus than other types of birds and that damage to the hippocampus causes impairments in spatial memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Some types of insects such as cockroaches, and molluscs such as the octopus, also have strong spatial learning and navigation abilities, but these appear to work differently from the mammalian spatial system, suggesting that there is no common evolutionary origin.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] Mushroom bodies in insect brains are associated with learning and memory carried out in the mammalian hippocampus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] The brain of the octopus is arranged in a circle of lobes around the esophagus.
[src:neuroanatomy/hippocampus-p02] The vertical lobe has been shown to be involved in forming long term memory, and is seen to be analogous to the mammalian hippocampus and cerebellum, and also to share some functional features of the mushroom bodies in insects.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The **limbic system**, also known as the **paleomammalian cortex**, is a set of brain structures involved in emotional processing and motivation in humans and many other animals.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] In humans it is located on both sides of the thalamus, immediately beneath the medial temporal lobe of the cerebrum primarily in the forebrain.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Its various components support a variety of functions including emotion, behavior, long-term memory, and olfaction.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The limbic system is involved in lower order emotional processing of input from sensory systems and consists of the amygdala, mammillary bodies, stria medullaris, central gray and dorsal and ventral nuclei of Gudden.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The limbic lobe was originally defined by the French anatomist Paul Broca in 1878, as a series of cortical structures surrounding the boundary between the cerebral hemispheres and the brainstem.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The name "limbic" comes from the Latin word for the border, *limbus*.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Further studies began to associate these areas with emotional and motivational processes and linked them to subcortical components that were then grouped into the limbic system.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] In recent years, multiple additional limbic fiber connectivity has been revealed using diffusion-weighted MRI.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The equivalent fiber connectivity of all these pathways has been documented by dissection studies in primates.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Some of these fiber tracts include the amygdalofugal tract, amygdalothalamic tract, stria terminalis, dorsal thalamo-hypothalamic tract, cerebellohypothalamic tracts, and the parieto-occipito-hypothalamic tract.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Currently, it is not considered an isolated entity responsible for the neurological regulation of emotion, but rather one of the many parts of the brain that regulate visceral autonomic processes.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Therefore, the set of anatomical structures considered part of the limbic system is controversial.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The structures and interacting areas of the limbic system are involved in motivation, emotion, learning, and memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The limbic system is where the subcortical structures meet the cerebral cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The limbic system operates by influencing the endocrine system and the autonomic nervous system.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] It is highly interconnected with the nucleus accumbens, which plays a role in sexual arousal and the "high" derived from certain recreational drugs.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] These responses are heavily modulated by dopaminergic projections from the limbic system.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] In 1954, Olds and Milner found that rats with metal electrodes implanted into their nucleus accumbens, as well as their septal nuclei, repeatedly pressed a lever activating this region.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The limbic system also interacts with the basal ganglia.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The basal ganglia are a set of subcortical structures that direct intentional movements.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The basal ganglia are located near the thalamus and hypothalamus.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] They receive input from the cerebral cortex, which sends outputs to the motor centers in the brain stem.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] A part of the basal ganglia called the striatum controls posture and movement.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Recent studies indicate that if there is an inadequate supply of dopamine in the striatum, this can lead to the symptoms of Parkinson's disease.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The limbic system is also tightly connected to the prefrontal cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] This connectivity has been demonstrated to play a role in memory consolidation, emotional processing, and interoception-driven behavior.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] To cure severe emotional disorders, this connection was sometimes surgically severed, a procedure of psychosurgery, called a prefrontal lobotomy (this is actually a misnomer).
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Patients having undergone this procedure often became passive and lacked all motivation.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The limbic system interacts heavily with the cerebral cortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] These interactions are closely linked to olfaction, emotions, drives, autonomic regulation, memory, and pathologically to encephalopathy, epilepsy, psychotic symptoms, cognitive defects.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The functional relevance of the limbic system has proven to serve many different functions such as affects/emotions, memory, sensory processing, time perception, attention, consciousness, instincts, autonomic/vegetative control, and actions/motor behavior.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Some of the disorders associated with the limbic system and its interacting components are epilepsy and schizophrenia.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The hippocampus is involved with various processes relating to cognition and is one of the best understood and heavily involved limbic interacting structures.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The first and most widely researched area concerns memory, particularly spatial memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Spatial memory was found to have many sub-regions in the hippocampus, such as the dentate gyrus (DG) in the dorsal hippocampus, the left hippocampus, and the parahippocampal region.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The dorsal hippocampus was found to be an important component for the generation of new neurons, called adult-born granules (GC), in adolescence and adulthood.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] These new neurons contribute to pattern separation in spatial memory, increasing the firing in cell networks, and overall causing stronger memory formations.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] This is thought to integrate spatial and episodic memories with the limbic system via a feedback loop that provides emotional context of a particular sensory input.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] While the dorsal hippocampus is involved in spatial memory formation, the left hippocampus is a participant in the recall of these spatial memories.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Eichenbaum and his team found, when studying the hippocampal lesions in rats, that the left hippocampus is "critical for effectively combining the 'what', 'when', and 'where' qualities of each experience to compose the retrieved memory".
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] This makes the left hippocampus a key component in the retrieval of spatial memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] However, Spreng found that the left hippocampus is a general concentrated region for binding together bits and pieces of memory composed not only by the hippocampus, but also by other areas of the brain to be recalled at a later time.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Eichenbaum's research in 2007 also demonstrates that the parahippocampal area of the hippocampus is another specialized region for the retrieval of memories just like the left hippocampus.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The hippocampus, over the decades, has also been found to have a huge impact in learning.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Curlik and Shors examined the effects of neurogenesis in the hippocampus and its effects on learning.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] This researcher and his team employed many different types of mental and physical training on their subjects, and found that the hippocampus is highly responsive to these latter tasks.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Thus, they discovered an upsurge of new neurons and neural circuits in the hippocampus as a result of the training, causing an overall improvement in the learning of the task.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] This neurogenesis contributes to the creation of adult-born granules cells (GC), cells also described by Eichenbaum in his own research on neurogenesis and its contributions to learning.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The creation of these cells exhibited "enhanced excitability" in the dentate gyrus (DG) of the dorsal hippocampus, impacting the hippocampus and its contribution to the learning process.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Damage related to the hippocampal region of the brain has reported vast effects on overall cognitive functioning, particularly memory such as spatial memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] As previously mentioned, spatial memory is a cognitive function greatly intertwined with the hippocampus.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] While damage to the hippocampus may be a result of a brain injury or other injuries of that sort, researchers particularly investigated the effects that high emotional arousal and certain types of drugs had on the recall ability in this specific memory type.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] In particular, in a study performed by Parkard, rats were given the task of correctly making their way through a maze.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] In the first condition, rats were stressed by shock or restraint which caused a high emotional arousal.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] When completing the maze task, these rats had an impaired effect on their hippocampal-dependent memory when compared to the control group.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Then, in a second condition, a group of rats were injected with anxiogenic drugs.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Like the former these results reported similar outcomes, in that hippocampal-memory was also impaired.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Studies such as these reinforce the impact that the hippocampus has on memory processing, in particular the recall function of spatial memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Furthermore, impairment to the hippocampus can occur from prolonged exposure to stress hormones such as glucocorticoids (GCs), which target the hippocampus and cause disruption in explicit memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] In an attempt to curtail life-threatening epileptic seizures, 27-year-old Henry Gustav Molaison underwent bilateral removal of almost all of his hippocampus in 1953.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Over the course of fifty years he participated in thousands of tests and research projects that provided specific information on exactly what he had lost.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Semantic and episodic events faded within minutes, having never reached his long-term memory, yet emotions, unconnected from the details of causation, were often retained.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Suzanne Corkin, who worked with him for 46 years until his death, described the contribution of this tragic "experiment" in her 2013 book.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Another integrative part of the limbic system, the amygdala, which is the deepest part of the limbic system, is involved in many cognitive processes and is largely considered the most primordial and vital part of the limbic system.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Like the hippocampus, processes in the amygdala seem to impact memory; however, it is not spatial memory as in the hippocampus but the semantic division of episodic-autobiographical memory (EAM) networks.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Markowitsch's amygdala research shows it encodes, stores, and retrieves EAM memories.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Neurons in the amygdala encode the valence and salience of fear and reward cues.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Limited research indicates that valence is encoded by non-overlapping cell populations in the amygdala, while salience is encoded by overlapping cell populations.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] These neurons project to various brain regions to modulate attention and motivated behavior, such as threat avoidance, reward seeking, and emotional memory acquisition.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] While the amygdala is involved in both fear- and reward-related behaviors, most research into this brain area focuses on its role in processing fear.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] For instance, the artificial activation or inhibition of the amygdala produces anxiolytic or anxiogenic behaviors, respectively.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Distinct cell populations in the amygdala encode fear memory, thereby being necessary for the acquisition of this form of memory.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Research efforts into the role of this signaling in neuropsychiatric disease have established its link to aberrant fear and anxiety.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] A separate population of amygdala neurons project to dopaminergic reward circuitry to mediate reward-associated memory, as cellular activity in this region encodes cues that predict reward.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Social processing, specifically the evaluation of faces in social processing, is an area of cognition specific to the amygdala.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] In a study done by Todorov, fMRI tasks were performed with participants to evaluate whether the amygdala was involved in the general evaluation of faces.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] After the study, Todorov concluded from his fMRI results that the amygdala did indeed play a key role in the general evaluation of faces.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] However, in a study performed by researchers Koscik and his team, the trait of trustworthiness was particularly examined in the evaluation of faces.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Koscik and his team demonstrated that the amygdala was involved in evaluating the trustworthiness of an individual.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] They investigated how brain damage to the amygdala played a role in trustworthiness, and found that individuals with damaged amygdalas tended to confuse trust and betrayal, and thus placed trust in those having done them wrong.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Furthermore, Rule, along with his colleagues, expanded on the idea of the amygdala in its critique of trustworthiness in others by performing a study in 2009 in which he examined the amygdala's role in evaluating general first impressions and relating them to real-world outcomes.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Their study involved first impressions of CEOs.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Rule demonstrated that while the amygdala did play a role in the evaluation of trustworthiness, as observed by Koscik in his own research two years later in 2011, the amygdala also played a generalized role in the overall evaluation of first impression of faces.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] This latter conclusion, along with Todorov's study on the amygdala's role in general evaluations of faces and Koscik's research on trustworthiness and the amygdala, further solidified evidence that the amygdala plays a role in overall social processing.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Based on experiments done on monkeys, the destruction of the temporal cortex almost always led to damage of the amygdala.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] This damage done to the amygdala led the physiologists Kluver and Bucy to pinpoint major changes in the behavior of the monkeys.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The monkeys would inspect and physically touch all objects placed in front of them.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The monkeys had a tendency to orally examine objects (e.g. biting, licking, etc.).
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The monkeys would respond, as if required to, to every stimulus (i.e.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The monkeys exhibited hypersexuality, demonstrating a sexual drive so strong that they would continuously stimulate their genitalia, copulate repeatedly and for long periods of time, and sometimes sustain small injuries in the process (e.g. due to excessive biting).
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] This set of behavioral change came to be known as the Klüver–Bucy syndrome.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] It may be considered a part of survival adaptation in reptiles as well as mammals (including humans).
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] MacLean postulated that the human brain has evolved three components, that evolved successively, with more recent components developing at the top/front.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The paleopallium or intermediate ("old mammalian") brain, comprising the structures of the limbic system.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The neopallium, also known as the superior or rational ("new mammalian") brain, comprises almost the whole of the hemispheres (made up of a more recent type of cortex, called neocortex) and some subcortical neuronal groups.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] It corresponds to the brain of the superior mammals, thus including the primates and, as a consequence, the human species.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Similar development of the neocortex in mammalian species not closely related to humans and primates has also occurred, for example in cetaceans and elephants; thus the designation of "superior mammals" is not an evolutionary one, as it has occurred independently in different species.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The evolution of higher degrees of intelligence is an example of convergent evolution, and is also seen in non-mammals such as birds.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] According to Maclean, each of the components, although connected with the others, retained "their peculiar types of intelligence, subjectivity, sense of time and space, memory, mobility and other less specific functions".
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] However, while the categorization into structures is reasonable, the recent studies of the limbic system of tetrapods, both living and extinct, have challenged several aspects of this hypothesis, notably the accuracy of the terms "reptilian" and "old mammalian".
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The common ancestors of reptiles and mammals had a well-developed limbic system in which the basic subdivisions and connections of the amygdalar nuclei were established.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Further, birds, which evolved from the dinosaurs, which in turn evolved separately but around the same time as the mammals, have a well-developed limbic system.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] While the anatomic structures of the limbic system are different in birds and mammals, there are functional equivalents.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The term *limbic* comes from the Latin *limbus*, for "border" or "edge", or, particularly in medical terminology, a border of an anatomical component.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Paul Broca coined the term based on its physical location in the brain, sandwiched between two functionally different components.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The limbic system is a term that was introduced in 1949 by the American physician and neuroscientist, Paul D.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The French physician Paul Broca first called this part of the brain *le grand lobe limbique* in 1878.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] He examined the differentiation between deeply recessed cortical tissue and underlying, subcortical nuclei.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] However, most of its putative role in emotion was developed only in 1937 when the American physician James Papez described his anatomical model of emotion, the Papez circuit.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The first evidence that the limbic system was responsible for the cortical representation of emotions was discovered in 1939, by Heinrich Kluver and Paul Bucy.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Kluver and Bucy, after much research, demonstrated that the bilateral removal of the temporal lobes in monkeys created an extreme behavioral syndrome.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] After performing a temporal lobectomy, the monkeys showed a decrease in aggression.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The animals revealed a reduced threshold to visual stimuli, and were thus unable to recognize objects that were once familiar.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] MacLean expanded these ideas to include additional structures in a more dispersed "limbic system", more on the lines of the system described above.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] MacLean developed the theory of the "triune brain" to explain its evolution and to try to reconcile rational human behavior with its more "primal" and "violent" side.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] He became interested in the brain's control of emotion and behavior.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] After initial studies of brain activity in epileptic patients, he turned to cats, monkeys, and other models, using electrodes to stimulate different parts of the brain in conscious animals recording their responses.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] In the 1950s, he began to trace individual behaviors like aggression and sexual arousal to their physiological sources.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] He postulated the limbic system as the brain's center of emotions, including the hippocampus and amygdala.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Developing observations made by Papez, he hypothesized that the limbic system had evolved in early mammals to control fight-or-flight responses and react to both emotionally pleasurable and painful sensations.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The concept is now broadly accepted in neuroscience.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] MacLean enlarged his theory to address the human brain's overall structure and divided its evolution into three parts, an idea that he termed the triune brain.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] In addition to identifying the limbic system, he hypothesized a supposedly more primitive brain called the R-complex, related to reptiles, which controls basic functions like muscle movement and breathing.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] According to him, the third part, the neocortex, controls speech and reasoning and is the most recent evolutionary arrival.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] The concept of the limbic system has since been further expanded and developed by Walle Nauta, Lennart Heimer, and others.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] There is controversy over the use of the term *limbic system*, with scientists such as Joseph E.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] LeDoux and Edmund Rolls arguing that the term be considered obsolete and abandoned.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Originally, the limbic system was believed to be the emotional center of the brain, with cognition being the business of the neocortex.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] However, cognition depends on acquisition and retention of memories, in which the hippocampus, a primary limbic interacting structure, is involved: hippocampus damage causes severe cognitive (memory) deficits.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] More important, the "boundaries" of the limbic system have been repeatedly redefined because of advances in neuroscience.
[src:neuroanatomy/limbic-system] Therefore, while it is true that limbic interacting structures are more closely related to emotion, the limbic system itself is best thought of as a component of a larger emotional processing plant.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] For information about the composition of non-human animal nervous systems, see nervous system.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] For information about the typical structure of the human nervous system, see human brain, and peripheral nervous system.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] The first known written record of a study of the anatomy of the human brain is an ancient Egyptian document, the Edwin Smith Papyrus.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] In Ancient Greece, interest in the brain began with the work of Alcmaeon, who appeared to have dissected the eye and related the brain to vision.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] He also suggested that the brain, not the heart, was the organ that ruled the body (what Stoics would call the *hegemonikon*) and that the senses were dependent on the brain.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] The debate regarding the *hegemonikon* persisted among ancient Greek philosophers and physicians for a very long time.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] Those who argued for the brain often contributed to the understanding of neuroanatomy as well.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] Herophilus and Erasistratus of Alexandria were perhaps the most influential with their studies involving dissecting human brains, affirming the distinction between the cerebrum and the cerebellum, and identifying the ventricles and the *dura mater*.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] The Greek physician and philosopher Galen, likewise, argued strongly for the brain as the organ responsible for sensation and voluntary motion, as evidenced by his research on the neuroanatomy of oxen, Barbary apes, and other animals.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] The cultural taboo on human dissection continued for several hundred years afterward, which brought no major progress in the understanding of the anatomy of the brain or of the nervous system.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] However, Pope Sixtus IV effectively revitalized the study of neuroanatomy by altering the papal policy and allowing human dissection.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] This resulted in a flush of new activity by artists and scientists of the Renaissance, such as Mondino de Luzzi, Berengario da Carpi, and Jacques Dubois, and culminating in the work of Andreas Vesalius.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] In 1664, Thomas Willis, a physician and professor at Oxford University, coined the term neurology when he published his text *Cerebri Anatome* which is considered the foundation of modern neuroanatomy.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] The subsequent three hundred and fifty some years has produced a great deal of documentation and study of the neural system.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] At the tissue level, the nervous system is composed of neurons, glial cells, and extracellular matrix.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] Both neurons and glial cells come in many types (see, for example, the nervous system section of the list of distinct cell types in the adult human body).
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] Glial cells maintain homeostasis, produce myelin (oligodendrocytes, Schwann cells), and provide support and protection for the brain's neurons.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] Some glial cells (astrocytes) can even propagate intercellular calcium waves over long distances in response to stimulation, and release gliotransmitters in response to changes in calcium concentration.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] Wound scars in the brain largely contain astrocytes.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] The extracellular matrix also provides support on the molecular level for the brain's cells, vehiculating substances to and from the blood vessels.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] At the organ level, the nervous system is composed of brain regions, such as the hippocampus in mammals or the mushroom bodies of the fruit fly.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] These regions are often modular and serve a particular role within the general systemic pathways of the nervous system.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] For example, the hippocampus is critical for forming memories in connection with many other cerebral regions.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] The peripheral nervous system also contains afferent or efferent nerves, which are bundles of fibers that originate from the brain and spinal cord, or from sensory or motor sorts of peripheral ganglia, and branch repeatedly to innervate every part of the body.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] Nerves are made primarily of the axons or dendrites of neurons (axons in case of efferent motor fibres, and dendrites in case of afferent sensory fibres of the nerves), along with a variety of membranes that wrap around and segregate them into nerve fascicles.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] The vertebrate nervous system is divided into the central and peripheral nervous systems.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] The central nervous system (CNS) consists of the brain, retina, and spinal cord, while the peripheral nervous system (PNS) is made up of all the nerves and ganglia (packets of peripheral neurons) outside of the CNS that connect it to the rest of the body.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] The PNS is further subdivided into the somatic and autonomic nervous systems.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] The somatic nervous system is made up of "afferent" neurons, which bring sensory information from the somatic (body) sense organs to the CNS, and "efferent" neurons, which carry motor instructions out to the voluntary muscles of the body.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] Autonomic nerves, unlike somatic nerves, contain only efferent fibers.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] Sensory signals coming from the viscera course into the CNS through the somatic sensory nerves (e.g., visceral pain), or through some particular cranial nerves (e.g., chemosensitive or mechanic signals).
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] In anatomy in general and neuroanatomy in particular, several sets of topographic terms are used to denote orientation and location, which are generally referred to the body or brain axis.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] The axis of the CNS is often wrongly assumed to be more or less straight, but it actually shows always two ventral flexures (cervical and cephalic flexures) and a dorsal flexure (pontine flexure), all due to differential growth during embryogenesis.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] Note that such descriptors (dorsal/ventral, rostral/caudal; medial/lateral) are relative rather than absolute (e.g., a lateral structure may be said to lie medial to something else that lies even more laterally).
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] Commonly used terms for planes of orientation or planes of section in neuroanatomy are "sagittal", "transverse" or "coronal", and "axial" or "horizontal".
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] Again in this case, the situation is different for swimming, creeping or quadrupedal (prone) animals than for Man, or other erect species, due to the changed position of the axis.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] Due to the axial brain flexures, no section plane ever achieves a complete section series in a selected plane, because some sections inevitably result cut oblique or even perpendicular to it, as they pass through the flexures.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] Experience allows to discern the portions that result cut as desired.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] According to these considerations, the three directions of space are represented precisely by the sagittal, transverse and horizontal planes, whereas coronal sections can be transverse, oblique or horizontal, depending on how they relate to the brain axis and its incurvations.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] Modern developments in neuroanatomy are directly correlated to the technologies used to perform research.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] Therefore, it is necessary to discuss the various tools that are available.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] Many of the histological techniques used to study other tissues can be applied to the nervous system as well.
[src:neuroanatomy/neuroanatomy] However, there are some techniques that have been developed especially for the study of neuroanatomy.
